00:03:53.160 --> 00:03:58.080
[Amit Varma]: Rahul, tell me a little bit about your background, like what were you trained as?

00:03:58.080 --> 00:04:00.280
[Amit Varma]: Were you an economist or social scientist?

00:04:00.280 --> 00:04:02.140
[Guest]: What got you into this field?

00:04:02.140 --> 00:04:04.160
[Guest]: So I'm a trained political scientist.

00:04:04.160 --> 00:04:07.640
[Guest]: I'm completing my PhD from University of California at Berkeley.

00:04:07.640 --> 00:04:12.040
[Guest]: Currently, I'm a fellow at the Center for Policy Research.

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:14.400
[Guest]: What got me interested into politics?

00:04:14.400 --> 00:04:16.080
[Guest]: Frankly, I don't know.

00:04:16.080 --> 00:04:20.840
[Guest]: I was interested in elections and politics as a child, perhaps.

00:04:20.840 --> 00:04:24.920
[Guest]: So as a child, I was sort of like, like most kids, I was a very naughty character.

00:04:24.920 --> 00:04:25.920
[Amit Varma]: Where was this?

00:04:25.920 --> 00:04:32.320
[Guest]: So I was born very close to Ayodhya, a small town in my village, which is very close to

00:04:32.320 --> 00:04:33.560
[Guest]: Ayodhya.

00:04:33.560 --> 00:04:41.120
[Guest]: So growing up, I basically witnessed two political phenomena that changed India forever.

00:04:41.120 --> 00:04:47.880
[Guest]: I didn't understand those two phenomena then, the Mandal politics as well as the Ram Mandir

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:48.880
[Guest]: politics.

00:04:48.880 --> 00:04:56.200
[Guest]: So literally, my first memory of Ram Mandir agitation and mobilization was that you can

00:04:56.200 --> 00:04:59.080
[Guest]: see buses with policemen.

00:04:59.080 --> 00:05:04.560
[Guest]: And all these policemen, what they do is basically eat banana and throw on the road.

00:05:04.560 --> 00:05:09.360
[Guest]: Later on, I figured out banana is a high energy fruit and you know, that's why these policemen

00:05:09.360 --> 00:05:10.360
[Guest]: eat it.

00:05:10.360 --> 00:05:13.040
[Guest]: So that's, that's my memory of a curfew.

00:05:13.040 --> 00:05:18.000
[Guest]: When when you see a curfew, you will see lots of policemen in buses and they will be basically

00:05:18.000 --> 00:05:20.640
[Guest]: eating bananas.

00:05:20.640 --> 00:05:25.560
[Guest]: So as a kid, I used to do all tamasha during the day.

00:05:25.560 --> 00:05:31.680
[Guest]: So during summer vacations, my father basically asked me to read newspapers.

00:05:31.680 --> 00:05:36.040
[Guest]: And in the evening, when he'll come back from his office, I have to tell him what is on

00:05:36.040 --> 00:05:39.420
[Guest]: the front page, what is on the sports space.

00:05:39.420 --> 00:05:47.320
[Guest]: And so I, as a child was just four, five or six, I started reading newspapers out of fear

00:05:47.320 --> 00:05:51.080
[Guest]: that I'll get sort of scolded in the evening if I don't do my homework.

00:05:51.080 --> 00:05:54.040
[Guest]: So I used to do a homework on newspapers.

00:05:54.040 --> 00:05:56.120
[Guest]: And I used to read.

00:05:56.120 --> 00:06:01.560
[Guest]: So because I was growing up in UP, at home, I was getting Hindi newspapers.

00:06:01.560 --> 00:06:08.200
[Guest]: So both on the sports page, as well as on politics page, I used to hear funny proper

00:06:08.200 --> 00:06:09.200
[Guest]: nouns, right?

00:06:09.200 --> 00:06:17.320
[Guest]: So in UP, there's a constituency near Mirzapur, which was Robert's ganj, you know, as a four

00:06:17.320 --> 00:06:21.480
[Guest]: or five year old kid, I was like, Roberts, I had heard in Hindi movies.

00:06:21.480 --> 00:06:27.920
[Guest]: So why is there a Robert's ganj, or if you read in the newspaper, all these terms are

00:06:27.920 --> 00:06:32.920
[Guest]: spelled very like, like before wicket is pagbada.

00:06:32.920 --> 00:06:40.840
[Guest]: And you know, these, these just used to sound funny in my head and and so I think that's

00:06:40.840 --> 00:06:47.160
[Guest]: how I got interested in politics, reading about them, sort of making a notebook both

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:48.200
[Guest]: of cricket scores.

00:06:48.200 --> 00:06:55.440
[Guest]: So cricket and politics both also have a component of numbers, if you win elections, you have

00:06:55.440 --> 00:06:56.980
[Guest]: to be right on the numbers.

00:06:56.980 --> 00:07:01.760
[Guest]: So I used to sort of maintain a notebook for a very long period of time on both cricket

00:07:01.760 --> 00:07:04.820
[Guest]: scores and on both political scores.

00:07:04.820 --> 00:07:07.600
[Guest]: And somehow, I think that got interested me in politics.

00:07:07.600 --> 00:07:12.600
[Amit Varma]: And do you think just thinking aloud, do you think that, unlike other English speaking

00:07:12.600 --> 00:07:17.400
[Amit Varma]: elites like myself, for that matter, who I mean, I grew up just reading English newspapers,

00:07:17.400 --> 00:07:22.120
[Amit Varma]: unfortunately, did the fact that you were reading Hindi newspapers day in and day out

00:07:22.120 --> 00:07:26.280
[Amit Varma]: since you were a kid, did that give you a slightly different understanding of politics

00:07:26.280 --> 00:07:28.680
[Amit Varma]: from the people who are your peers today?

00:07:28.680 --> 00:07:34.240
[Guest]: So I don't know that, but even today, I order a Hindi newspaper.

00:07:34.240 --> 00:07:39.360
[Guest]: And if you look at Hindi newspapers, their coverage is very different from what you get

00:07:39.360 --> 00:07:41.160
[Guest]: in English newspapers.

00:07:41.160 --> 00:07:46.440
[Guest]: So I don't know about a different perspective, but I certainly get to see more things than

00:07:46.440 --> 00:07:49.000
[Guest]: what get covered in a Hindi newspaper.

00:07:49.000 --> 00:07:55.880
[Guest]: The editorials in Hindi newspapers are very, very different on very different subjects.

00:07:55.880 --> 00:08:01.480
[Guest]: And I remember, a couple of years ago, there was a debate in a couple of English newspapers

00:08:01.480 --> 00:08:07.200
[Guest]: by Ram Guha, Sagarika and other people basically writing on this topic.

00:08:07.200 --> 00:08:12.360
[Guest]: Why don't we have conservative public intellectuals?

00:08:12.360 --> 00:08:16.400
[Guest]: And my answer was, perhaps you don't read vernacular newspapers.

00:08:16.400 --> 00:08:18.040
[Guest]: Because your point is we do.

00:08:18.040 --> 00:08:19.040
[Guest]: We do.

00:08:19.040 --> 00:08:20.960
[Guest]: They just don't write in English.

00:08:20.960 --> 00:08:24.040
[Guest]: If you read Marathi newspapers, if you read Kannada newspapers.

00:08:24.040 --> 00:08:29.080
[Guest]: So in fact, because I have been reading Hindi newspapers, so I know Hindi public intellectuals

00:08:29.080 --> 00:08:31.360
[Guest]: who have conservative viewpoint.

00:08:31.360 --> 00:08:35.600
[Guest]: And then I asked my other friends who read Marathi or Kannada newspapers, and they said

00:08:35.600 --> 00:08:37.560
[Guest]: we do have these things.

00:08:37.560 --> 00:08:44.160
[Guest]: So I think certainly, you get a very different point of view by reading vernacular language

00:08:44.160 --> 00:08:45.360
[Amit Varma]: newspapers.

00:08:45.360 --> 00:08:49.720
[Amit Varma]: So you know, as you as you kind of grow up, and then you got into the academics of it

00:08:49.720 --> 00:08:55.200
[Amit Varma]: as well, who are the sort of thinkers who influence the way you think about politics

00:08:55.200 --> 00:08:56.200
[Amit Varma]: in the world?

00:08:56.200 --> 00:09:00.440
[Amit Varma]: Are there any books that you can recommend to my listeners or books that you feel changed

00:09:00.440 --> 00:09:01.680
[Guest]: the way you think about the world?

00:09:01.680 --> 00:09:08.720
[Guest]: There is a long list of both thinkers and books that have influenced me.

00:09:08.720 --> 00:09:13.640
[Guest]: I so I'm a political science or politics nerd.

00:09:13.640 --> 00:09:21.760
[Guest]: So you know, I read things, I don't know, but there's no time of either reading or sort

00:09:21.760 --> 00:09:24.360
[Guest]: of like working on things.

00:09:24.360 --> 00:09:31.240
[Guest]: But so if you think of good Indian political scientists who people should read, perhaps

00:09:31.240 --> 00:09:40.200
[Guest]: in the older generation, Rajnikothari, Randhir Singh, who was a big Marxist theorist.

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:45.000
[Guest]: If you to read contemporary people, I think Pratap Bhanu Mehta who writes in Indian Express

00:09:45.000 --> 00:09:48.360
[Guest]: is one of our foremost political philosophers.

00:09:48.360 --> 00:09:56.000
[Guest]: I think Yogendra Yadav still, when he sort of like, despite being in politics, I think

00:09:56.000 --> 00:09:59.320
[Guest]: some of his writings are very illuminating.

00:09:59.320 --> 00:10:05.800
[Guest]: There were some social scientists who were American, but they worked on India, Myron

00:10:05.800 --> 00:10:13.240
[Guest]: Weiner's work on Congress Party, child in the state, migration and nativism.

00:10:13.240 --> 00:10:19.760
[Guest]: I think Suzanne and Lloyd Rudolph's work on the political economy of India.

00:10:19.760 --> 00:10:25.680
[Guest]: So there are lots of political scientists who have influenced.

00:10:25.680 --> 00:10:29.320
[Guest]: I think I also read a lot of Hindi fiction.

00:10:29.320 --> 00:10:36.440
[Guest]: So if people want to sort of like, Raag Darbari is one classic Shrilal Shukla, but Mela Achal,

00:10:36.440 --> 00:10:40.200
[Guest]: we were talking about Kashi Nath Singh.

00:10:40.200 --> 00:10:50.400
[Guest]: So one advice which I got from my PhD advisor, that if you're not getting idea, read fiction.

00:10:50.400 --> 00:10:54.640
[Guest]: So don't read too much political science, but also read fiction.

00:10:54.640 --> 00:11:01.160
[Guest]: And I think fiction, poetry makes you think about things in a very different context.

00:11:01.160 --> 00:11:07.160
[Guest]: So I love reading poetry, I grew up in a small village, but my schooling was from Lucknow.

00:11:07.160 --> 00:11:08.960
[Guest]: So there is some influence of Lucknow.

00:11:08.960 --> 00:11:18.440
[Guest]: I think even like, I have always been fascinated by two line share or six line couplets, which

00:11:18.440 --> 00:11:25.080
[Guest]: basically tries to bring a very, very complex thought into, say, 10 or 12 words, right.

00:11:25.080 --> 00:11:30.520
[Guest]: So I do think people, perhaps Dhumil, I don't know, there have been so many poets who have

00:11:30.520 --> 00:11:36.240
[Guest]: influenced me, generally, I think.

00:11:36.240 --> 00:11:44.440
[Guest]: So I don't read much political philosophy, perhaps later in my life, I'll do that.

00:11:44.440 --> 00:11:50.000
[Guest]: But as part of course, curriculums, I have read, I think, Hobbes, Rousseau, Locke, and

00:11:50.000 --> 00:11:55.520
[Guest]: all of these have made influential points.

00:11:55.520 --> 00:12:03.880
[Guest]: What books people should read, I think, read as much as you can.

00:12:03.880 --> 00:12:12.480
[Guest]: And just look at like top 50 novels in your language, which you are comfortable with or

00:12:12.480 --> 00:12:16.080
[Guest]: top 50 novels in English.

00:12:16.080 --> 00:12:19.800
[Guest]: I don't know what names to give to you.

00:12:19.800 --> 00:12:20.800
[Amit Varma]: But...

00:12:20.800 --> 00:12:21.800
[Amit Varma]: No, fair enough.

00:12:21.800 --> 00:12:26.520
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, what you said definitely strikes a chord with me, because I haven't read remotely

00:12:26.520 --> 00:12:28.480
[Amit Varma]: as much in Hindi as you obviously have.

00:12:28.480 --> 00:12:34.240
[Amit Varma]: But, you know, if someone were to ask me, how do we understand India of the 1960s and

00:12:34.240 --> 00:12:35.240
[Amit Varma]: 70s?

00:12:35.240 --> 00:12:37.360
[Amit Varma]: And I would say there is no better book than Raag Darbari.

00:12:37.360 --> 00:12:39.560
[Amit Varma]: How do we understand the nature of the Indian state?

00:12:39.560 --> 00:12:42.200
[Amit Varma]: I would say there is no better book than Raag Darbari.

00:12:42.200 --> 00:12:46.240
[Amit Varma]: You can pick up books by historians and political theorists and all that.

00:12:46.240 --> 00:12:52.000
[Amit Varma]: But the sort of magic in a good work of fiction that, you know, capture society and Raag Darbari

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:55.880
[Amit Varma]: incidentally is available on Storytel, who are the sponsors right now of The Seen and

00:12:55.880 --> 00:12:56.880
[Amit Varma]: the Unseen.

00:12:56.880 --> 00:13:02.080
[Amit Varma]: So you can actually listen to it in Hindi over there, even if you're not comfortable

00:13:02.080 --> 00:13:03.080
[Amit Varma]: reading the language.

00:13:03.080 --> 00:13:08.240
[Amit Varma]: So sort of moving on from there, you know, let's come to the book that we're talking

00:13:08.240 --> 00:13:13.080
[Amit Varma]: about, which you've co-written with Pradeep Chhibber, Ideological Identity.

00:13:13.080 --> 00:13:15.200
[Guest]: How did you come to this subject?

00:13:15.200 --> 00:13:21.280
[Guest]: So Pradeep Chhibber, he's my PhD advisor, he's a professor of political science at University

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:23.760
[Guest]: of California, Berkeley.

00:13:23.760 --> 00:13:29.900
[Guest]: Pradeep is considered one of the foremost experts on party politics and party systems.

00:13:29.900 --> 00:13:35.320
[Guest]: And he has written some very interesting books on party systems.

00:13:35.320 --> 00:13:41.200
[Guest]: But before this book, he wrote another book, which I think didn't get attention.

00:13:41.200 --> 00:13:44.860
[Guest]: The title of the book is Religious Practice and Democracy in India.

00:13:44.860 --> 00:13:50.800
[Guest]: And what he shows in that book, that religious practice in India, especially the public.

00:13:50.800 --> 00:13:54.400
[Guest]: So this is all based on data, survey data.

00:13:54.400 --> 00:14:01.600
[Guest]: So people who go to, say, religious sites such as temples, gurudwaras, mosques, churches,

00:14:01.600 --> 00:14:08.320
[Guest]: and people who participate in religious services, such as bhajan, kirtans, and jalsas, and chur

00:14:08.320 --> 00:14:14.120
[Guest]: services, their outlook towards democracy is much more positive than those who don't

00:14:14.120 --> 00:14:15.800
[Guest]: practice religion.

00:14:15.800 --> 00:14:24.440
[Guest]: And idea is basically that all other sources, which links individuals to the state are sort

00:14:24.440 --> 00:14:25.440
[Guest]: of captured.

00:14:25.440 --> 00:14:30.760
[Guest]: So if you think of or captured or not working properly, right, basically, you have a capricious

00:14:30.760 --> 00:14:36.720
[Guest]: state in India, bureaucracy is discretionary and sort of like discriminates, political

00:14:36.720 --> 00:14:39.320
[Guest]: parties have been captured by vested interest.

00:14:39.320 --> 00:14:47.680
[Guest]: It is religion or religious places, which even for moments, provides equality to people

00:14:47.680 --> 00:14:49.600
[Guest]: from all walks of life.

00:14:49.600 --> 00:14:54.240
[Guest]: And that's why those who participate in it, they think that the democracy in the country

00:14:54.240 --> 00:14:56.820
[Guest]: is functioning much better.

00:14:56.820 --> 00:15:03.600
[Guest]: So Pradeep generally, and I think this is largely, I wouldn't say a norm, but slowly

00:15:03.600 --> 00:15:10.800
[Guest]: getting more traction, that in natural sciences or in engineering people, they don't write

00:15:10.800 --> 00:15:17.240
[Guest]: solo author pieces, you will always see 5, 6, 8, 10 people writing this.

00:15:17.240 --> 00:15:21.240
[Guest]: Social sciences was generally where people were doing solo work.

00:15:21.240 --> 00:15:27.160
[Guest]: But nowadays, given this lot more emphasis on sort of like data related work, and this

00:15:27.160 --> 00:15:31.760
[Guest]: basically brings much more collaboration than earlier.

00:15:31.760 --> 00:15:37.160
[Guest]: And there, I think I see much more collaborative work happening between not just professors,

00:15:37.160 --> 00:15:40.320
[Guest]: but professors and their mentees and students.

00:15:40.320 --> 00:15:44.200
[Guest]: So Pradeep generally works with all of his students.

00:15:44.200 --> 00:15:49.320
[Guest]: So I am not an exception to the large community of scholars.

00:15:49.320 --> 00:15:53.760
[Guest]: He has been sort of producing in last 20 odd years.

00:15:53.760 --> 00:15:58.720
[Guest]: So we were writing couple of op-eds and Pradeep generally likes to take a walk when he wants

00:15:58.720 --> 00:16:00.360
[Guest]: to discuss something, right?

00:16:00.360 --> 00:16:02.800
[Guest]: So he loves running.

00:16:02.800 --> 00:16:08.720
[Guest]: And so I think this was around Independence Day, we were in Berkeley, and somehow the

00:16:08.720 --> 00:16:15.760
[Guest]: conversation started happening that there is a long shadow of partition, right?

00:16:15.760 --> 00:16:23.200
[Guest]: The same themes emerging every five, six years, the debate on majoritarianism or how to accommodate

00:16:23.200 --> 00:16:29.600
[Guest]: religious minorities into body politic, the debate on reservation resonates every time.

00:16:29.600 --> 00:16:33.240
[Guest]: So we thought that and these were some of the founding debates we were having at the

00:16:33.240 --> 00:16:34.960
[Guest]: time of independence.

00:16:34.960 --> 00:16:39.360
[Guest]: And so I think the idea started germinating from there.

00:16:39.360 --> 00:16:47.400
[Guest]: So during the 2014 elections, what we did is wrote series of op-eds on six, seven chapters,

00:16:47.400 --> 00:16:49.120
[Guest]: which you see in the book.

00:16:49.120 --> 00:16:53.400
[Guest]: Basically we tested our idea in 1,200 words each.

00:16:53.400 --> 00:16:59.160
[Guest]: And once we got enough reactions, so we did start with the classic economic and social

00:16:59.160 --> 00:17:01.280
[Guest]: ideology framework.

00:17:01.280 --> 00:17:02.800
[Guest]: That's where we started.

00:17:02.800 --> 00:17:06.920
[Guest]: And in the data, there wasn't any difference in the economic, so there was a difference

00:17:06.920 --> 00:17:10.380
[Guest]: on the social ideology or social conservatism.

00:17:10.380 --> 00:17:15.760
[Guest]: But between parties, there was no difference on the economic ideology front.

00:17:15.760 --> 00:17:20.840
[Guest]: And then we started wondering why we don't see the other dimension, which is so much

00:17:20.840 --> 00:17:24.720
[Guest]: prevalent in Western Europe and North America.

00:17:24.720 --> 00:17:30.040
[Guest]: And that got us into thinking, perhaps either our polity is one dimensional, or there is

00:17:30.040 --> 00:17:35.440
[Guest]: a second dimension, but there is something unique about our own historical and cultural

00:17:35.440 --> 00:17:36.880
[Guest]: context.

00:17:36.880 --> 00:17:41.280
[Guest]: And we started reading about things and that's how the collaborative process began.

00:17:41.280 --> 00:17:45.080
[Amit Varma]: I was struck by a quote, which actually comes towards the end of your book, but kind of

00:17:45.080 --> 00:17:48.640
[Amit Varma]: sums up the conventional wisdom which your book is questioning.

00:17:48.640 --> 00:17:54.320
[Amit Varma]: And it's a quote from the Italian Giovano Sartori, quote, ideology does not strike roots

00:17:54.320 --> 00:17:55.800
[Amit Varma]: in all types of soil.

00:17:55.800 --> 00:17:59.640
[Amit Varma]: And while there is very little evidence to the effect that ideological factors do have

00:17:59.640 --> 00:18:04.320
[Amit Varma]: empirical relevance in African context, it is abundantly clear that most of what is spoken

00:18:04.320 --> 00:18:09.560
[Amit Varma]: as ideology is mere political rhetoric, and at the same time image selling to Western

00:18:09.560 --> 00:18:10.560
[Amit Varma]: public.

00:18:10.560 --> 00:18:11.560
[Amit Varma]: Stop quote.

00:18:11.560 --> 00:18:12.560
[Amit Varma]: And this applies to India as well.

00:18:12.560 --> 00:18:18.240
[Amit Varma]: And early on in your introduction, you guys write, quote, contemporary Indian Party politics

00:18:18.240 --> 00:18:24.960
[Amit Varma]: is commonly viewed as chaotic, centered around leaders, corrupt, volatile, and non ideological

00:18:24.960 --> 00:18:26.000
[Amit Varma]: in nature.

00:18:26.000 --> 00:18:30.000
[Amit Varma]: What accounts for this perception and for the corollary view that elections in India

00:18:30.000 --> 00:18:37.840
[Amit Varma]: are really, if ever, genuine contest of ideas, policies, and visions, stop quote.

00:18:37.840 --> 00:18:42.920
[Amit Varma]: So why does this perception then then kind of exist?

00:18:42.920 --> 00:18:51.000
[Guest]: So the couple of so, apart from this quote, there was another interesting, I think letter

00:18:51.000 --> 00:18:58.140
[Guest]: to the editor in New York Times or somewhere where someone basically went on a rant that,

00:18:58.140 --> 00:19:05.240
[Guest]: you know, Indian political parties are just alphabets, one lot siding with the other lot.

00:19:05.240 --> 00:19:10.720
[Guest]: It's not a solemn selection of leader of 1.3 billion, but like a children's game show.

00:19:10.720 --> 00:19:17.200
[Guest]: But if you if you remember, 2014 election or 2019 election, both the Congress Party

00:19:17.200 --> 00:19:23.760
[Guest]: leaders, the top leaders in the Congress Party, as well as BJP leaders was, in fact, unequivocally

00:19:23.760 --> 00:19:31.140
[Guest]: saying that this is a fight or battle for the soul of India, or this is a fight between

00:19:31.140 --> 00:19:32.800
[Guest]: two ideas of India.

00:19:32.800 --> 00:19:37.920
[Guest]: So politicians perhaps realize these are ideological battles.

00:19:37.920 --> 00:19:45.020
[Guest]: But in our scholarly context, journalistic context, we thought voters do not.

00:19:45.020 --> 00:19:48.600
[Guest]: So there is no structure or framework to our politics.

00:19:48.600 --> 00:19:55.480
[Guest]: People just vote on their whims, or they get something, and in exchange of those favors,

00:19:55.480 --> 00:19:59.680
[Guest]: they vote particular political party or politician.

00:19:59.680 --> 00:20:02.320
[Guest]: So we don't want to go that route.

00:20:02.320 --> 00:20:07.780
[Guest]: And we tried to avoid as much as we could, we didn't want to go on a rant against this

00:20:07.780 --> 00:20:13.060
[Guest]: whole perception of that Indian politics is non ideological.

00:20:13.060 --> 00:20:22.420
[Guest]: But we do wanted to make a point that any departure from how politics is conducted in

00:20:22.420 --> 00:20:30.680
[Guest]: best is seen as primordial, or the politics in West is structured around ideas, whereas

00:20:30.680 --> 00:20:36.640
[Guest]: politics in developing world is just taking some samosas, some liquor, some sari and voting

00:20:36.640 --> 00:20:38.840
[Amit Varma]: for the tribal instincts and so on.

00:20:38.840 --> 00:20:45.160
[Guest]: So we were sort of like bugged with this sort of characterization of about Indian politics.

00:20:45.160 --> 00:20:50.880
[Guest]: And this is what is Giovanni Sartori is one of the foremost political scientists, he's

00:20:50.880 --> 00:20:52.720
[Guest]: a classic on party systems.

00:20:52.720 --> 00:20:59.520
[Guest]: And I like his writing, when I read this stuff, I thought this should go in our book, because

00:20:59.520 --> 00:21:06.720
[Guest]: this is what we are sort of like, challenging that we may not developing countries like

00:21:06.720 --> 00:21:11.520
[Guest]: India or postcolonial countries like India may not have the same structure of politics

00:21:11.520 --> 00:21:13.160
[Guest]: as the West.

00:21:13.160 --> 00:21:19.240
[Guest]: But the departure should not be understood as these countries, there is no framework

00:21:19.240 --> 00:21:21.120
[Guest]: to our politics.

00:21:21.120 --> 00:21:27.760
[Guest]: So I think that was sort of like beginning of why we wanted to sort of take on on this

00:21:27.760 --> 00:21:28.760
[Guest]: argument.

00:21:28.760 --> 00:21:34.680
[Guest]: The perception has remained is I think, what we would like to describe as a fake fact of

00:21:34.680 --> 00:21:35.680
[Guest]: politics.

00:21:35.680 --> 00:21:38.280
[Guest]: And there is no basis to make that claim.

00:21:38.280 --> 00:21:45.200
[Guest]: But once that claim started gaining ground, it became sort of a truism or a normal assumption

00:21:45.200 --> 00:21:46.520
[Amit Varma]: about our politics.

00:21:46.520 --> 00:21:52.880
[Amit Varma]: No, and what it strikes me and this is even a mere culpa of sorts in the sense that this

00:21:52.880 --> 00:21:57.240
[Amit Varma]: perception this looking at Indian politics through a left right prism through a fundamentally

00:21:57.240 --> 00:22:01.560
[Amit Varma]: Western prism and saying that, oh, okay, it doesn't function along this prism.

00:22:01.560 --> 00:22:07.320
[Amit Varma]: Therefore, it is sort of non ideological, and it's on all these other factors, which

00:22:07.320 --> 00:22:12.200
[Amit Varma]: is one that I've held for so long, and your book is making me reconsider really comes

00:22:12.200 --> 00:22:18.760
[Amit Varma]: from mostly from political thinkers or theorists or columnists or pundits who are a part of

00:22:18.760 --> 00:22:23.240
[Amit Varma]: the English speaking elite whose education is kind of Western, whether it is in the West

00:22:23.240 --> 00:22:24.280
[Amit Varma]: or here.

00:22:24.280 --> 00:22:28.120
[Amit Varma]: And as you pointed out earlier in the episode, you've grown up reading Hindi newspapers,

00:22:28.120 --> 00:22:31.880
[Amit Varma]: and therefore it's you weren't exactly captured by the elite in that sense.

00:22:31.880 --> 00:22:37.960
[Amit Varma]: You also had access to expressions of different contestations and, you know, a different set

00:22:37.960 --> 00:22:41.240
[Amit Varma]: of intellectuals from where you came.

00:22:41.240 --> 00:22:47.000
[Amit Varma]: Before we kind of proceed by talking about the book, I think it's kind of useful to define

00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:49.520
[Amit Varma]: some of the terms because they get confusing you.

00:22:49.520 --> 00:22:51.520
[Guest]: So for example, define ideology.

00:22:51.520 --> 00:22:52.520
[Guest]: Okay.

00:22:52.520 --> 00:22:57.500
[Guest]: Well, I just wanted to sort of get back to one point, which is basically this departure

00:22:57.500 --> 00:23:00.920
[Guest]: from the West.

00:23:00.920 --> 00:23:08.360
[Guest]: Democracy is sort of understood and defined very differently in the context of West, whereas

00:23:08.360 --> 00:23:13.880
[Guest]: democracy in the context of postcolonial and underdeveloped countries is always defined

00:23:13.880 --> 00:23:16.480
[Guest]: with an adjective, right?

00:23:16.480 --> 00:23:20.560
[Guest]: That is, this is not a perfect democracy, it has become an ethnic democracy, it has

00:23:20.560 --> 00:23:22.440
[Guest]: become something like that.

00:23:22.440 --> 00:23:29.040
[Guest]: If you come to think of it, India is one of the busiest laboratories of democratic politics.

00:23:29.040 --> 00:23:35.160
[Guest]: And I think now, so in US, when we used to make presentations, not just me, but many

00:23:35.160 --> 00:23:41.040
[Guest]: times, if people who work on South Asia or Africa or some other country, there would

00:23:41.040 --> 00:23:42.040
[Guest]: be a general question.

00:23:42.040 --> 00:23:44.160
[Guest]: And this is a legitimate question.

00:23:44.160 --> 00:23:48.080
[Guest]: How far does your theory travel to other parts of the world?

00:23:48.080 --> 00:23:53.480
[Guest]: And sometimes in my irritation, I used to basically, if not in public, I do used to

00:23:53.480 --> 00:23:56.800
[Guest]: say that I don't care if it doesn't travel.

00:23:56.800 --> 00:24:00.540
[Guest]: In every theory, we own one sixth, right?

00:24:00.540 --> 00:24:08.800
[Guest]: So given the size of our population, we now need to sort of like the theory of democracy

00:24:08.800 --> 00:24:15.760
[Guest]: now needs to move out from the best West and see how it is being practiced in a country

00:24:15.760 --> 00:24:22.240
[Guest]: like India, or Bangladesh, or say, Philippines, and those theories now sort of like needs

00:24:22.240 --> 00:24:23.240
[Guest]: revision.

00:24:23.240 --> 00:24:24.920
[Amit Varma]: And no, I get what you're saying.

00:24:24.920 --> 00:24:28.440
[Amit Varma]: And there's a certain condescension there from people on the West who are sort of saying

00:24:28.440 --> 00:24:31.840
[Amit Varma]: that, here's our theory and our theory is paramount.

00:24:31.840 --> 00:24:32.840
[Amit Varma]: And does it fit you?

00:24:32.840 --> 00:24:33.920
[Amit Varma]: Or does it not?

00:24:33.920 --> 00:24:37.160
[Amit Varma]: And but asking different questions of your theory, where you actually have to kind of

00:24:37.160 --> 00:24:42.320
[Amit Varma]: prove that it travels, as you said, which I can understand why you were irritated by

00:24:42.320 --> 00:24:43.320
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:24:43.320 --> 00:24:47.320
[Amit Varma]: So let's go to ideology, let's talk about, you know, since your book is centered around

00:24:47.320 --> 00:24:49.600
[Amit Varma]: ideology, define it for me.

00:24:49.600 --> 00:24:55.880
[Guest]: So we take a very sort of like watertight definition of what we consider as ideological

00:24:55.880 --> 00:25:02.480
[Guest]: conflict, right, which is basically issue bundle.

00:25:02.480 --> 00:25:06.320
[Guest]: And many of these issues go together.

00:25:06.320 --> 00:25:10.040
[Guest]: And voters take basically position on on these issues.

00:25:10.040 --> 00:25:16.120
[Guest]: So it might happen that you care about one issue more than the other, but because it

00:25:16.120 --> 00:25:23.200
[Guest]: is part of your issue bundle, you will have some position closer to your preference.

00:25:23.200 --> 00:25:30.280
[Guest]: But for anything to become ideological and structure party politics, we claim that it

00:25:30.280 --> 00:25:32.680
[Guest]: must meet four conditions.

00:25:32.680 --> 00:25:38.480
[Guest]: One, every election can have a very different issue, which drives that election.

00:25:38.480 --> 00:25:44.200
[Guest]: But for something to become the basis of ideological conflict, it needs to be stable for a long

00:25:44.200 --> 00:25:46.160
[Guest]: period of time.

00:25:46.160 --> 00:25:50.400
[Guest]: Because it is an idea, it must have an intellectual origin.

00:25:50.400 --> 00:25:59.440
[Guest]: There must be people or intellectuals, elites, writing about it, debating about it and talking

00:25:59.440 --> 00:26:00.440
[Guest]: about it.

00:26:00.440 --> 00:26:04.480
[Guest]: So the second criteria is it must have an intellectual basis.

00:26:04.480 --> 00:26:11.600
[Guest]: Third, to reach that idea to masses, it needs channels of transmission from political or

00:26:11.600 --> 00:26:14.000
[Guest]: social elites to masses.

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:21.040
[Guest]: Fourth, it must have enough number of people on each side of the divide, because unless

00:26:21.040 --> 00:26:28.160
[Guest]: that happens, you won't see political parties taking a clear stand on any on that issue.

00:26:28.160 --> 00:26:31.520
[Guest]: And that wouldn't become a basis of ideological conflict.

00:26:31.520 --> 00:26:39.440
[Guest]: And I think to think about why we make this argument that the Indian version of ideological

00:26:39.440 --> 00:26:46.920
[Guest]: conflict is very different, because those ideas are born out of historical experiences

00:26:46.920 --> 00:26:48.400
[Guest]: and trajectories.

00:26:48.400 --> 00:26:53.560
[Guest]: And the historical experience of the West and the postcolonial country, like India was

00:26:53.560 --> 00:26:55.020
[Guest]: very, very different.

00:26:55.020 --> 00:26:59.500
[Guest]: And that's why our ideological conflict are going to be very, very different.

00:26:59.500 --> 00:27:03.640
[Amit Varma]: And that's a very fascinating part of your book where you kind of elaborate on the four

00:27:03.640 --> 00:27:07.840
[Amit Varma]: different ways in which ideology as the West understands it is formed in the West and why

00:27:07.840 --> 00:27:12.440
[Amit Varma]: none of those apply to India because of a completely different set of circumstances

00:27:12.440 --> 00:27:13.440
[Amit Varma]: and histories.

00:27:13.440 --> 00:27:15.280
[Guest]: Can you elaborate on what those four ways are?

00:27:15.280 --> 00:27:21.560
[Guest]: So this is a very famous thesis by Lipset and Roca and those are two great political

00:27:21.560 --> 00:27:23.760
[Guest]: scientists.

00:27:23.760 --> 00:27:31.800
[Guest]: So the claim they make that the West European party system is frozen in four cleavages.

00:27:31.800 --> 00:27:39.240
[Guest]: The four cleavages were basically labor versus capital, rural versus urban, center versus

00:27:39.240 --> 00:27:42.180
[Guest]: periphery and church versus state.

00:27:42.180 --> 00:27:48.280
[Guest]: Those were the four sort of like main cleavages on which party politics in West Europe happened.

00:27:48.280 --> 00:27:54.940
[Guest]: And it happened because West Europe underwent a historical trajectory of first renaissance,

00:27:54.940 --> 00:27:58.220
[Guest]: reformation, then industrial revolution.

00:27:58.220 --> 00:28:01.420
[Guest]: Industrial revolution produced capital, labor divide.

00:28:01.420 --> 00:28:07.280
[Guest]: It also, because of industrial revolution, it also created an urban-rural divide.

00:28:07.280 --> 00:28:11.940
[Guest]: There was always a center-periphery issue going on in many parts of those countries

00:28:11.940 --> 00:28:16.180
[Guest]: and the church and state thing comes from renaissance and reformation.

00:28:16.180 --> 00:28:20.620
[Guest]: A country like India never underwent this historical experience.

00:28:20.620 --> 00:28:26.700
[Guest]: Overnight, we became an independent nation-state from a colony.

00:28:26.700 --> 00:28:32.940
[Guest]: So for us, while nation-building debates were happening in the background, but we suddenly

00:28:32.940 --> 00:28:38.060
[Guest]: become an independent or sovereign country within a matter of night.

00:28:38.060 --> 00:28:45.020
[Guest]: And at the time of independence, most of these countries like India were so poor, so rural

00:28:45.020 --> 00:28:48.500
[Guest]: that you cannot have a politics on these cleavages.

00:28:48.500 --> 00:28:54.140
[Guest]: In fact, when Nehru stands in the Constituent Assembly to begin the objective resolution,

00:28:54.140 --> 00:29:00.220
[Guest]: he basically begins with that the first task of this assembly is to clothe the naked, feed

00:29:00.220 --> 00:29:01.220
[Guest]: the hungry.

00:29:01.220 --> 00:29:06.660
[Guest]: So the state, in a sense, there was a consensus that the state is going to take the burden

00:29:06.660 --> 00:29:08.100
[Guest]: of poor, right?

00:29:08.100 --> 00:29:11.700
[Guest]: And that's why we don't see divide on economic ideology.

00:29:11.700 --> 00:29:16.140
[Guest]: There may be minor differences on the route to welfare model.

00:29:16.140 --> 00:29:23.820
[Guest]: But I don't think any political party, as you said, in India is pro-market in that sense,

00:29:23.820 --> 00:29:24.820
[Guest]: right?

00:29:24.820 --> 00:29:29.740
[Guest]: We don't have market versus state debate among our political parties, barring, I think, the

00:29:29.740 --> 00:29:35.780
[Guest]: communist parties, which has a clear, at least written prescription, but I don't know whether

00:29:35.780 --> 00:29:39.140
[Guest]: they follow the same thing on the ground.

00:29:39.140 --> 00:29:43.100
[Guest]: So the two axes could not have, so they didn't take off.

00:29:43.100 --> 00:29:46.420
[Guest]: The center-periphery debate could have taken off.

00:29:46.420 --> 00:29:52.700
[Guest]: And there were riot-like situation, in fact, on the question of integration of various

00:29:52.700 --> 00:29:54.360
[Guest]: parts of India.

00:29:54.360 --> 00:30:03.280
[Guest]: And I think that problem got in some ways resolved by the reorganization of state into

00:30:03.280 --> 00:30:05.280
[Guest]: linguistic provinces.

00:30:05.280 --> 00:30:13.700
[Guest]: So language, politics now was just centered within the state, not vis-a-vis the center.

00:30:13.700 --> 00:30:20.740
[Guest]: So I think there were some steps taken in 1950s and 60s, which restricted the center-state

00:30:20.740 --> 00:30:27.780
[Guest]: fight emerging as a central issue of, basically, as a national issue in that sense.

00:30:27.780 --> 00:30:29.100
[Guest]: It remained localized.

00:30:29.100 --> 00:30:37.220
[Guest]: So you would see in Tamil Nadu, a fight with Delhi or in Jammu Kashmir, a fight with Delhi,

00:30:37.220 --> 00:30:42.700
[Guest]: but that does not become a mobilizing plank across India, especially in the large parts

00:30:42.700 --> 00:30:44.300
[Guest]: of Hindi heartland.

00:30:44.300 --> 00:30:52.060
[Guest]: The fourth, in India, we never had that kind of centralized church, Hinduism never had

00:30:52.060 --> 00:30:53.060
[Guest]: that kind of...

00:30:53.060 --> 00:30:54.700
[Amit Varma]: It's very diffused, almost outsourced.

00:30:54.700 --> 00:31:00.500
[Guest]: Yes, so we never had a church versus, at the time of independence, there was no church

00:31:00.500 --> 00:31:03.500
[Guest]: versus state conflict that was happening.

00:31:03.500 --> 00:31:12.540
[Guest]: But we could in some way, sort of like, argue that religion or accommodation of religious

00:31:12.540 --> 00:31:18.580
[Guest]: minorities did become a meta-narrative of Indian politics, and it does resonate still

00:31:18.580 --> 00:31:19.580
[Guest]: today.

00:31:19.580 --> 00:31:24.980
[Amit Varma]: Right, so you kind of pointed out and I found your arguments quite convincing and obviously

00:31:24.980 --> 00:31:30.260
[Amit Varma]: agree with them that these four sort of ideological cleavages of the West don't apply to India.

00:31:30.260 --> 00:31:34.460
[Amit Varma]: However, you said this does not mean that India does not have ideological contestations

00:31:34.460 --> 00:31:40.060
[Amit Varma]: and you talk about two specific ideological battlegrounds, which have been ideological

00:31:40.060 --> 00:31:44.060
[Amit Varma]: battlegrounds for decades, and therefore they are stable and they meet all your other conditions

00:31:44.060 --> 00:31:48.300
[Amit Varma]: of the ideology that they are stable, they have intellectual elites on both sides, they

00:31:48.300 --> 00:31:52.020
[Amit Varma]: are propagated through all the various kinds of means.

00:31:52.020 --> 00:31:53.340
[Amit Varma]: Tell me what those two are.

00:31:53.340 --> 00:32:01.300
[Guest]: So we basically argue that Indian politics is structured by two ideological scales.

00:32:01.300 --> 00:32:09.700
[Guest]: One, we describe it as politics of recognition, which is basically the idea of bringing different

00:32:09.700 --> 00:32:15.060
[Guest]: groups into the body politic and what would be the method of accommodation.

00:32:15.060 --> 00:32:21.780
[Guest]: So debates on reservations and quota, whether the Indian state should hew to majoritarian

00:32:21.780 --> 00:32:28.460
[Guest]: characteristic, that basically forms the bulk of basis of politics of recognition.

00:32:28.460 --> 00:32:33.580
[Guest]: And if you read the Constituent Assembly debates, these were the questions on which our founding

00:32:33.580 --> 00:32:38.460
[Guest]: fathers, there were very few women in the Constituent Assembly, so founding fathers

00:32:38.460 --> 00:32:40.100
[Guest]: were debating about.

00:32:40.100 --> 00:32:46.540
[Guest]: The debate on cow slaughter, like I think began in 1909 or something, where members

00:32:46.540 --> 00:32:51.980
[Guest]: in the Constituent Assembly are quoting statistics that there were so many thousand cows in the

00:32:51.980 --> 00:32:57.100
[Guest]: northwestern frontier provinces, and now their population has decreased to this.

00:32:57.100 --> 00:33:03.700
[Guest]: And that's why there is a cow slaughter happening, they will invoke Gandhiji and you know, Constituent

00:33:03.700 --> 00:33:06.300
[Guest]: Assembly, you were having these things.

00:33:06.300 --> 00:33:13.320
[Guest]: Similarly, the debate on reservations started way back in 18, I think 1882.

00:33:13.320 --> 00:33:21.460
[Guest]: So there were some ramblings earlier also in Mysore, in Kolhapur and in Trivandrum.

00:33:21.460 --> 00:33:27.620
[Guest]: But in 1882, I think Hunter Commission, so there was a representation by Fule to Hunter

00:33:27.620 --> 00:33:33.860
[Guest]: Commission for affirmative action for Dalits and backwards in the education sector.

00:33:33.860 --> 00:33:38.060
[Guest]: And I think that debate on reservations began there.

00:33:38.060 --> 00:33:43.540
[Guest]: Then it took another shape during the Monte Merlo reforms, Monge Uchemsford reforms, Gandhi

00:33:43.540 --> 00:33:49.740
[Guest]: Ambedkar debate, a large part of Constituent Assembly debates were on the reservations,

00:33:49.740 --> 00:33:52.380
[Guest]: 1950s Kalelkar.

00:33:52.380 --> 00:34:00.380
[Guest]: So I think throughout the last hundred years, we had spurts of moments where the debate

00:34:00.380 --> 00:34:03.500
[Guest]: on reservations were happening for different communities.

00:34:03.500 --> 00:34:10.980
[Guest]: And I think now with the BJP's final, so in fact, the reservation bill for economically

00:34:10.980 --> 00:34:15.340
[Guest]: weaker section, this is the first time it has been passed.

00:34:15.340 --> 00:34:20.420
[Guest]: But at different times, various governments have tried to bring this bill, which is what

00:34:20.420 --> 00:34:26.220
[Guest]: it is doing is changing the nature of the debate on reservation from sort of historical

00:34:26.220 --> 00:34:30.020
[Guest]: reparation and social justice to economic backwardness.

00:34:30.020 --> 00:34:36.660
[Guest]: So so there's a very different twist that is being given by BJP on the reservation.

00:34:36.660 --> 00:34:41.620
[Amit Varma]: In fact, this particular twist is almost one which takes it from your first ideological

00:34:41.620 --> 00:34:46.620
[Amit Varma]: cleavage, which is to do with recognition to your second one, which is to do with statism.

00:34:46.620 --> 00:34:53.620
[Amit Varma]: So not necessarily, but again, about the state sort of remaking the economy or society by

00:34:53.620 --> 00:34:56.740
[Guest]: this kind of.

00:34:56.740 --> 00:35:02.300
[Guest]: So we have a very particular understanding of what do we mean by statism.

00:35:02.300 --> 00:35:08.500
[Guest]: And I do acknowledge that it may not fully encapsulate what is happening.

00:35:08.500 --> 00:35:15.420
[Guest]: So in our view, the role of the state in society has a very different conception in Western

00:35:15.420 --> 00:35:18.780
[Guest]: political thought and Indian political thought.

00:35:18.780 --> 00:35:25.080
[Guest]: In the West, society basically makes the state to sort of like reorganize it.

00:35:25.080 --> 00:35:30.240
[Guest]: So that's the Hobbes, Locke, Rousseau tradition, whereas if you read Indian political thinkers

00:35:30.240 --> 00:35:35.700
[Guest]: and the classic textbooks such as sort of like Mahabharata, Shastra.

00:35:35.700 --> 00:35:43.500
[Guest]: So I think the state society conception in Indian political thought is very, very different.

00:35:43.500 --> 00:35:49.300
[Guest]: And perhaps there is a reason why we don't have a good theory of state and we don't have

00:35:49.300 --> 00:35:51.100
[Guest]: a good theory of kingship.

00:35:51.100 --> 00:35:58.300
[Guest]: In fact, in all our texts, there is things written about what a good king should do and

00:35:58.300 --> 00:36:00.060
[Guest]: what a bad king would do.

00:36:00.060 --> 00:36:02.500
[Guest]: But why do we need a king?

00:36:02.500 --> 00:36:07.300
[Guest]: The theory of kingship is not well established in Indian political thought.

00:36:07.300 --> 00:36:13.020
[Guest]: So the way these most of these thinkers, not just limited to the Hindu tradition, but it

00:36:13.020 --> 00:36:16.120
[Guest]: seems like a subcontinental idea.

00:36:16.120 --> 00:36:21.740
[Guest]: And you find resonance of this in some ways in Buddhist thought, Islamic thoughts, as

00:36:21.740 --> 00:36:28.140
[Guest]: well as in Hinduism, where the role of the state or the king is to act as the guardian

00:36:28.140 --> 00:36:29.800
[Guest]: of the society.

00:36:29.800 --> 00:36:36.660
[Guest]: So the state and king cannot sort of like, they should protect the social norms, but

00:36:36.660 --> 00:36:41.620
[Guest]: they should not be trying to remake the society.

00:36:41.620 --> 00:36:47.300
[Guest]: And they should not even sort of like have redistributive impulse, basically taking away

00:36:47.300 --> 00:36:49.700
[Guest]: property and then redistributive.

00:36:49.700 --> 00:36:56.300
[Guest]: In fact, if you think about Gandhian idea of trusteeship, it was based on the same notion.

00:36:56.300 --> 00:37:01.620
[Guest]: This is not the job of the state to take away property from people who have it.

00:37:01.620 --> 00:37:05.180
[Guest]: And so basically changing social economic norms.

00:37:05.180 --> 00:37:09.940
[Guest]: And I think, and this is what emerges from Constituent Assembly debates and debates that

00:37:09.940 --> 00:37:17.620
[Guest]: were happening on a Hindu court bill at that moment of time, was that people like Ambedkar

00:37:17.620 --> 00:37:25.260
[Guest]: and Nehru wanted to use the levers of the state to remove the inequalities in our social

00:37:25.260 --> 00:37:27.020
[Guest]: and economic life.

00:37:27.020 --> 00:37:34.100
[Guest]: And then there were other members in the Constituent Assembly who were opposed to these ideas.

00:37:34.100 --> 00:37:39.220
[Guest]: They thought that this is not the job of the state to remake the society.

00:37:39.220 --> 00:37:43.980
[Amit Varma]: And like you explained in your book, it comes, I mean, this whole conflict in a sense comes

00:37:43.980 --> 00:37:50.240
[Amit Varma]: from differing perceptions of what is the relationship between the state and the society.

00:37:50.240 --> 00:37:55.020
[Amit Varma]: As you say in your book, quote, in Western political theory, Rousseau, Locke and Hegel

00:37:55.020 --> 00:37:56.740
[Amit Varma]: are good examples.

00:37:56.740 --> 00:38:00.940
[Amit Varma]: Political order means a subjugation of society to the state.

00:38:00.940 --> 00:38:04.860
[Amit Varma]: So you know, you might have a state of nature there, but for society to function, you need

00:38:04.860 --> 00:38:07.700
[Amit Varma]: the state to protect individual rights and so on.

00:38:07.700 --> 00:38:09.460
[Amit Varma]: That's Western political theory.

00:38:09.460 --> 00:38:14.480
[Amit Varma]: But to give the contrast to that with what is contained in Indian conservative thought,

00:38:14.480 --> 00:38:20.540
[Amit Varma]: you quote Karpatri Maharaj and I'll quote this Karpatri Maharaj's words, quote, in Indian

00:38:20.540 --> 00:38:26.240
[Amit Varma]: tradition, the society is always supreme and the ruler is accountable to dharma and society.

00:38:26.240 --> 00:38:30.620
[Amit Varma]: The administrator and administration keep changing, but not the society and dharma.

00:38:30.620 --> 00:38:35.100
[Amit Varma]: The laws of the state always have to be favorable to religious texts, stop quote.

00:38:35.100 --> 00:38:41.100
[Amit Varma]: So in that conception, society already exists, it is prior to the state.

00:38:41.100 --> 00:38:46.500
[Amit Varma]: And then the state comes in and the state is like sort of an administrative convenience.

00:38:46.500 --> 00:38:47.740
[Guest]: That's absolutely correct.

00:38:47.740 --> 00:38:52.780
[Guest]: So so in this conception, the role of the state is just a facilitator.

00:38:52.780 --> 00:38:55.560
[Guest]: There is permanent feature, which is society.

00:38:55.560 --> 00:39:01.460
[Guest]: And the interesting feature about this whole conception is that there may be some sort

00:39:01.460 --> 00:39:06.540
[Guest]: of like deformation or bad things that may appear in the society.

00:39:06.540 --> 00:39:13.100
[Guest]: Now that the state should not be sort of intervening to remove those bad things, the society would

00:39:13.100 --> 00:39:17.300
[Guest]: itself heal up or will come up with solution.

00:39:17.300 --> 00:39:18.300
[Guest]: Right.

00:39:18.300 --> 00:39:21.460
[Guest]: So so think about the problem of untouchability, right?

00:39:21.460 --> 00:39:27.380
[Guest]: Gandhi never said the state to sort of like, take the law in hand and remove untouchability.

00:39:27.380 --> 00:39:31.660
[Guest]: He basically goes in the society and says, this is a bad thing, we need to reform it.

00:39:31.660 --> 00:39:32.660
[Guest]: Right.

00:39:32.660 --> 00:39:38.860
[Guest]: So so in this framework, or the model, the reform has to come within the society, the

00:39:38.860 --> 00:39:44.300
[Guest]: state should not be using a violent mean or a danda to sort of like, correct things.

00:39:44.300 --> 00:39:49.140
[Amit Varma]: In fact, one of my favorite quotes about politics is by Andrew Breitbart, where he says, politics

00:39:49.140 --> 00:39:51.020
[Amit Varma]: is downstream of culture.

00:39:51.020 --> 00:39:54.900
[Amit Varma]: And it would seem that that represents sort of the traditional Indian view.

00:39:54.900 --> 00:40:00.900
[Amit Varma]: And it's also very interesting that then the people fighting for statism, as it were, the

00:40:00.900 --> 00:40:05.580
[Amit Varma]: state intervening in the economy and in society, were essentially Western educated liberals

00:40:05.580 --> 00:40:07.260
[Guest]: like Nehru and Ambedkar.

00:40:07.260 --> 00:40:08.260
[Guest]: That is correct.

00:40:08.260 --> 00:40:09.260
[Guest]: That is correct.

00:40:09.260 --> 00:40:11.780
[Guest]: And Karpatri Maharaj, he's a very interesting character.

00:40:11.780 --> 00:40:15.860
[Guest]: And I hope some political theorist works on him.

00:40:15.860 --> 00:40:19.220
[Guest]: So Karpatri Maharaj was the founder of Ram Rajya Parishad.

00:40:19.220 --> 00:40:26.220
[Guest]: This was an orthodox Hindu party in 1950s, which slowly sort of got merged into Bharatiya

00:40:26.220 --> 00:40:27.300
[Guest]: Jan Sangh.

00:40:27.300 --> 00:40:30.460
[Guest]: So the quotes are coming from Karpatri Maharaj.

00:40:30.460 --> 00:40:34.940
[Guest]: He wrote, I think, more than 1000 page book.

00:40:34.940 --> 00:40:39.380
[Guest]: And the name of the book is Marx Vada or Ram Raj.

00:40:39.380 --> 00:40:45.500
[Guest]: And he basically is sort of like, challenging not just the Marxist interpretation of the

00:40:45.500 --> 00:40:52.460
[Guest]: state and society, but he takes on all possible Western philosophers in that.

00:40:52.460 --> 00:40:58.580
[Guest]: And a lot of it is, in some ways, you can call it basically polemic and rhetoric.

00:40:58.580 --> 00:41:06.500
[Guest]: But then somebody sitting in the jail and writing these 1000 pages as Indian political

00:41:06.500 --> 00:41:07.500
[Unknown]: thought.

00:41:07.500 --> 00:41:08.700
[Guest]: Is a translation of it available?

00:41:08.700 --> 00:41:13.420
[Guest]: So I have not seen the English translation, I've seen the Hindi one, and it is sold by

00:41:13.420 --> 00:41:14.420
[Guest]: Gita Press.

