[Amit Varma]: So that should be fairly interesting.

00:41:39.260 --> 00:41:44.980
[Amit Varma]: And then you've got another quote from Gandhi, quoted by Massani, but a quote from Gandhi

00:41:44.980 --> 00:41:49.700
[Amit Varma]: in your book, which is, quote, I look upon an increase in the power of the state with

00:41:49.700 --> 00:41:54.540
[Amit Varma]: the greatest fear, because although apparently doing good by minimizing exploitation, it

00:41:54.540 --> 00:42:00.100
[Amit Varma]: does the greatest harm to mankind by destroying individuality, which lies at the root of all

00:42:00.100 --> 00:42:02.140
[Amit Varma]: progress, stop quote.

00:42:02.140 --> 00:42:06.220
[Amit Varma]: And you know, here he's almost coming down on the side of the traditionalists.

00:42:06.220 --> 00:42:10.900
[Amit Varma]: And so tell me a little bit, so these are the two sort of ideological contestations

00:42:10.900 --> 00:42:11.900
[Amit Varma]: you've identified.

00:42:11.900 --> 00:42:13.980
[Amit Varma]: There is a politics of recognition.

00:42:13.980 --> 00:42:16.580
[Amit Varma]: And there is a politics of statism.

00:42:16.580 --> 00:42:19.820
[Amit Varma]: Let's talk about both in turn, let's talk about statism first.

00:42:19.820 --> 00:42:24.980
[Amit Varma]: What are the sort of debates taking place around statism at the time of the Constituent

00:42:24.980 --> 00:42:25.980
[Amit Varma]: Assembly?

00:42:25.980 --> 00:42:29.460
[Amit Varma]: Because it's not as if Gandhi and Ambedkar are getting their view, there's a pushback.

00:42:29.460 --> 00:42:31.460
[Amit Varma]: And in fact, the cover of your book is really fascinating.

00:42:31.460 --> 00:42:35.460
[Amit Varma]: As you pointed out, it's a picture of Nehru's first cabinet.

00:42:35.460 --> 00:42:41.300
[Amit Varma]: And the fascinating point you made is that if you just look at them, you know, left to

00:42:41.300 --> 00:42:45.940
[Amit Varma]: right, they almost represent where they stand ideologically with Nehru in the center, Shyama

00:42:45.940 --> 00:42:51.620
[Amit Varma]: Prasad Mukherjee on the extreme right, and then you have Vallabhbhai Patel and Rajendra

00:42:51.620 --> 00:42:52.660
[Amit Varma]: Prasad.

00:42:52.660 --> 00:42:54.860
[Amit Varma]: And on the extreme left, you have Dr. Bhimrao Ambedkar.

00:42:54.860 --> 00:43:01.100
[Amit Varma]: And on the extreme left, you have Dr. Ambedkar and almost representing sort of the very two

00:43:01.100 --> 00:43:06.860
[Amit Varma]: cleavages that you talk about, you know, where you could say that the guys on the right like

00:43:06.860 --> 00:43:12.300
[Amit Varma]: Shyama Prasad and are against the sort of statism and the intervention that these guys

00:43:12.300 --> 00:43:13.300
[Amit Varma]: do.

00:43:13.300 --> 00:43:17.380
[Amit Varma]: And the guys like you get to the left, you get to Ambedkar and that's probably the extreme

00:43:17.380 --> 00:43:23.260
[Amit Varma]: when it comes to recognition, though, not remotely as extreme as so many people today,

00:43:23.260 --> 00:43:24.260
[Amit Varma]: which is quite interesting.

00:43:24.260 --> 00:43:26.620
[Amit Varma]: Tell me about the battles around statism.

00:43:26.620 --> 00:43:35.940
[Guest]: So if you think of 1940s and 50s, statism basically implies using the power of the state

00:43:35.940 --> 00:43:38.940
[Guest]: to change social and economic norms.

00:43:38.940 --> 00:43:48.460
[Guest]: By social norms, you can take, for example, marriage norms, inheritance norm, and economic

00:43:48.460 --> 00:43:51.580
[Guest]: would be, say, redistribution of private property.

00:43:51.580 --> 00:43:57.260
[Guest]: Now, the best example of this debate could be found in the debates that were taking place

00:43:57.260 --> 00:43:59.460
[Guest]: on the Hindu Code Bill.

00:43:59.460 --> 00:44:07.580
[Guest]: In fact, there was so much vociferous opposition to the Hindu Code Bill that the debate started

00:44:07.580 --> 00:44:16.580
[Guest]: in, I think, 1940s and it ends in 1956, when Nehru, in fact, had to break down the Hindu

00:44:16.580 --> 00:44:22.060
[Guest]: Code Bill into four parts and then get it passed through the parliament.

00:44:22.060 --> 00:44:26.700
[Guest]: But before that, I would sort of like the hell broke loose.

00:44:26.700 --> 00:44:32.100
[Guest]: Ambedkar thought that Nehru is not serious enough on the Hindu Code Bill because he thought

00:44:32.100 --> 00:44:37.900
[Guest]: this is very, very important to give women equal place in the society.

00:44:37.900 --> 00:44:42.700
[Guest]: And given Nehru's non-seriousness on the matter, he, in fact, resigned from Nehru's cabinet.

00:44:42.700 --> 00:44:49.020
[Guest]: Nehru had different plans and didn't sort of talk, took Ambedkar in confidence on that.

00:44:49.020 --> 00:44:56.300
[Guest]: But before this Gandhi-Nehru-Ambedkar battle, Purushottam Das Tandon, in 1953, became the

00:44:56.300 --> 00:44:58.380
[Guest]: president of the Congress Party.

00:44:58.380 --> 00:45:03.380
[Guest]: And he was one of the traditionalists who was opposed to the Hindu Code Bill.

00:45:03.380 --> 00:45:08.540
[Guest]: And Nehru knew with him being the president of the Congress Party, this would not work.

00:45:08.540 --> 00:45:15.180
[Guest]: And in a way, Nehru had to revolt, use his charismatic personality and power of the prime

00:45:15.180 --> 00:45:19.020
[Guest]: minister to sort of ask Purushottam Das Tandon to step down.

00:45:19.020 --> 00:45:23.620
[Guest]: So there was battle within the Congress Party, within the government on this question of

00:45:23.620 --> 00:45:24.740
[Guest]: Hindu Code Bill.

00:45:24.740 --> 00:45:26.260
[Guest]: And what was Hindu Code Bill?

00:45:26.260 --> 00:45:32.900
[Guest]: Basically, trying to sort of like codify marriage and inheritance norms.

00:45:32.900 --> 00:45:38.820
[Guest]: And similarly, on the question of redistribution of private property, both, I think, Nehru

00:45:38.820 --> 00:45:46.460
[Guest]: had not just the instincts, but he pushed for reforms, land reforms, right?

00:45:46.460 --> 00:45:51.240
[Guest]: And look at the kind of opposition it met.

00:45:51.240 --> 00:45:53.860
[Guest]: There was sort of a compromise on this.

00:45:53.860 --> 00:46:00.500
[Guest]: India was, I think, one of the first countries to have right to property as fundamental rights.

00:46:00.500 --> 00:46:05.260
[Guest]: And this was a sort of like pushback traditionalists gave back in the Constituent Assembly that

00:46:05.260 --> 00:46:08.260
[Guest]: they got right to private property as a fundamental right.

00:46:08.260 --> 00:46:15.260
[Guest]: And Nehru, on the other hand, wanted to push the land reforms and in some ways it failed.

00:46:15.260 --> 00:46:19.540
[Guest]: So those were like two big debates that happened in 1950s.

00:46:19.540 --> 00:46:22.620
[Amit Varma]: And now, of course, the right to property is no longer a fundamental right.

00:46:22.620 --> 00:46:26.580
[Amit Varma]: And this is something I had an episode on with Shruti Rajgopal.

00:46:26.580 --> 00:46:31.020
[Amit Varma]: And I think it's episode 26, commend me for my memory, episode 26 of the scene and the

00:46:31.020 --> 00:46:32.020
[Amit Varma]: unseen.

00:46:32.020 --> 00:46:33.020
[Amit Varma]: I'll link it from the show notes.

00:46:33.020 --> 00:46:39.940
[Amit Varma]: And it's interesting how both Karpatri Maharaj and Maulana Madhuri, one of the founding thinkers

00:46:39.940 --> 00:46:46.300
[Amit Varma]: of Islamism, both opposed this kind of redistribution and this kind of statism.

00:46:46.300 --> 00:46:49.740
[Amit Varma]: And you kind of wonder, you know, when you talk about, and this is a question I ask many

00:46:49.740 --> 00:46:55.180
[Amit Varma]: of my guests, that when we debate sort of the idea of India, that fine, you know, Nehru's

00:46:55.180 --> 00:47:00.180
[Amit Varma]: idea of India, some of which I agree with, some of which I don't agree with, but Nehru's

00:47:00.180 --> 00:47:08.500
[Amit Varma]: idea of India won out in those founding years, partly because he happened to be a giant of

00:47:08.500 --> 00:47:09.500
[Amit Varma]: the freedom movement.

00:47:09.500 --> 00:47:11.020
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, he was in that position.

00:47:11.020 --> 00:47:17.100
[Amit Varma]: And partly because of happenstance that other figures from within his party, like the traditionalist

00:47:17.100 --> 00:47:23.100
[Amit Varma]: Hindu wing of his party sort of got sidelined after Vallabhbhai Patel died in 1950.

00:47:23.100 --> 00:47:27.700
[Amit Varma]: And, you know, he made Pushyantanda stand and step down because he wanted Kripalani

00:47:27.700 --> 00:47:32.900
[Amit Varma]: to be Congress president and that wing kind of just faded away.

00:47:32.900 --> 00:47:39.540
[Amit Varma]: But my question is this, that before we arrive at what the idea of India should be, and it's

00:47:39.540 --> 00:47:46.420
[Amit Varma]: basically a bunch of elites debating that and deciding that, it is also perhaps interesting

00:47:46.420 --> 00:47:53.420
[Amit Varma]: to question what is India, and should the idea of India reflect what India is?

00:47:53.420 --> 00:47:57.180
[Amit Varma]: And did that idea of India reflect what India was?

00:47:57.180 --> 00:48:03.180
[Amit Varma]: I mean, you know, later on in time, Dindayal Upadhyay made the point that the constitution

00:48:03.180 --> 00:48:08.580
[Amit Varma]: does not reflect India, that it's been foisted by sort of liberal, Western elites and so

00:48:08.580 --> 00:48:09.580
[Amit Varma]: on.

00:48:09.580 --> 00:48:13.180
[Amit Varma]: And this is then a question that I've asked various people on this podcast, including

00:48:13.180 --> 00:48:16.740
[Amit Varma]: Suryash, including Shashi Tharoor a while back and various people.

00:48:16.740 --> 00:48:23.220
[Amit Varma]: So I'll ask you now that, you know, how do we resolve this, that let's say that, you

00:48:23.220 --> 00:48:28.660
[Amit Varma]: know, we might welcome the idea of a liberal constitution, but if the liberal constitution

00:48:28.660 --> 00:48:35.940
[Amit Varma]: is something imposed by elites, by liberal elites on a country which is fundamentally

00:48:35.940 --> 00:48:40.700
[Amit Varma]: illiberal, and I don't necessarily use that in a bad way, but which is fundamentally not

00:48:40.700 --> 00:48:44.460
[Amit Varma]: liberal, then is that imposition itself not illiberal?

00:48:44.460 --> 00:48:50.340
[Guest]: That's a good question, complicated question.

00:48:50.340 --> 00:48:52.380
[Guest]: And I don't think I have a good answer to it.

00:48:52.380 --> 00:48:53.380
[Guest]: But let me try.

00:48:53.380 --> 00:48:54.380
[Guest]: I think so.

00:48:54.380 --> 00:49:01.980
[Guest]: First, we must remember, so this idea of India term got popularized by Khilani's book.

00:49:01.980 --> 00:49:08.140
[Guest]: But and I think one doesn't need to do a very careful reading, just a cursory reading will

00:49:08.140 --> 00:49:15.420
[Guest]: tell you that Khilani talks about ideas of India, he basically says that there were multiple

00:49:15.420 --> 00:49:20.020
[Guest]: ideas of India, the idea of India makes the case.

00:49:20.020 --> 00:49:24.960
[Guest]: And that's why he's writing about it, because he thinks the idea of India represents the

00:49:24.960 --> 00:49:33.980
[Guest]: diversity of not just the diversity of the population, but only the idea of India allows

00:49:33.980 --> 00:49:37.100
[Guest]: all other ideas to exist simultaneously.

00:49:37.100 --> 00:49:43.940
[Guest]: So so so in that sense, not just diversity, but pluralism, where you sort of like multiple

00:49:43.940 --> 00:49:49.060
[Guest]: it is multiplicity of thoughts can sort of coexist.

00:49:49.060 --> 00:49:57.260
[Guest]: And perhaps we should in the book in the conclusion, and this is a sort of like a thought experiment

00:49:57.260 --> 00:50:05.100
[Guest]: we borrowed from Ashutosh Vashney, which is basically think of like 1940s India, on you

00:50:05.100 --> 00:50:16.340
[Guest]: had three strong contenders for power, Vallabhbhai Patel on one hand, and Nehru on the in between,

00:50:16.340 --> 00:50:22.900
[Guest]: and then you have Bose on the other hand, Bose and Patel, both were very, very popular

00:50:22.900 --> 00:50:29.180
[Guest]: and charismatic leaders, and they had big organizational influence, Bose Gandhi debate

00:50:29.180 --> 00:50:33.580
[Guest]: of 1930s when Bose became the president of the Congress Party.

00:50:33.580 --> 00:50:39.900
[Guest]: So so so so Vashney in his book basically writes that one shudders to think what would

00:50:39.900 --> 00:50:45.620
[Guest]: have happened to India, if instead of Nehru, Bose or Patel would have become the Prime

00:50:45.620 --> 00:50:48.800
[Guest]: Minister, first Prime Minister of the country.

00:50:48.800 --> 00:50:54.940
[Guest]: So I think, depending upon your ideological position today, you would have a point of

00:50:54.940 --> 00:50:57.700
[Guest]: view on that particular question.

00:50:57.700 --> 00:51:07.420
[Guest]: But I think in a diverse country like India, the passing of Baten from Britishers and and

00:51:07.420 --> 00:51:15.340
[Guest]: basically to the liberal elite, it allowed India to remain democratic, perhaps with some

00:51:15.340 --> 00:51:17.920
[Guest]: deficiencies and everything.

00:51:17.920 --> 00:51:24.540
[Guest]: But if we would have gone other way, and by that I don't mean Bose or Patel.

00:51:24.540 --> 00:51:30.980
[Guest]: But if a conservative politician would have sort of like, got the Baten, I think the very

00:51:30.980 --> 00:51:34.420
[Guest]: much idea of democracy in India would have been in danger.

00:51:34.420 --> 00:51:42.140
[Guest]: So this counterfactual thought experiment, I sort of like tells me that, okay, there

00:51:42.140 --> 00:51:50.460
[Guest]: were the discourse in the beginning was dominated by liberal elite, who sort of presented them

00:51:50.460 --> 00:51:53.140
[Guest]: as patrons of masses.

00:51:53.140 --> 00:51:58.500
[Guest]: But in doing so, at least they germinated the idea of democracy in our country.

00:51:58.500 --> 00:52:03.380
[Amit Varma]: No, and there's a fascinating insight in that thought experiment, in the sense that as you

00:52:03.380 --> 00:52:08.060
[Amit Varma]: correctly pointed out that of all the ideas of India, which could have won out, there

00:52:08.060 --> 00:52:13.120
[Amit Varma]: is only one idea of India, which would have allowed the others to contest it and emerge.

00:52:13.120 --> 00:52:18.060
[Amit Varma]: So today, if you have say, some would argue that the idea of India, which is on the ascendant

00:52:18.060 --> 00:52:22.180
[Amit Varma]: today is not just the idea of Narendra Modi, but also the idea of Vallabhbhai Patel and

00:52:22.180 --> 00:52:26.940
[Amit Varma]: this is maybe the direction he would have liked to take India in though I don't think

00:52:26.940 --> 00:52:29.380
[Amit Varma]: that's exactly correct, but some would make that point.

00:52:29.380 --> 00:52:36.180
[Amit Varma]: Then the point to be made there is that other idea has emerged and triumphed in our democracy,

00:52:36.180 --> 00:52:40.380
[Amit Varma]: because we first ensured that it was a liberal democracy to begin with.

00:52:40.380 --> 00:52:44.140
[Amit Varma]: That's actually the most satisfying answer of all the ones that my guests have given

00:52:44.140 --> 00:52:45.140
[Amit Varma]: me so far.

00:52:45.140 --> 00:52:51.100
[Amit Varma]: You've kind of described the sort of the contestations around statism.

00:52:51.100 --> 00:52:56.340
[Amit Varma]: Before we go in for a break, tell me a little bit about the contestations around recognition.

00:52:56.340 --> 00:53:02.500
[Guest]: So I think we discussed some of it, especially on the reservation debate, but also on the

00:53:02.500 --> 00:53:08.140
[Guest]: question of majoritarianism, which is basically whether the Indian state should queue to majoritarian

00:53:08.140 --> 00:53:16.380
[Guest]: tendencies, or it should become more accommodative of religious minorities.

00:53:16.380 --> 00:53:24.900
[Guest]: I think we didn't do enough justice on that question in terms of like, there was ambivalent

00:53:24.900 --> 00:53:28.260
[Guest]: in the position of leaders at the time of independence.

00:53:28.260 --> 00:53:31.220
[Guest]: And I think that's what ideological conflict do, right?

00:53:31.220 --> 00:53:35.900
[Guest]: It allows you to sort of like, mitigate on certain questions, but on other questions,

00:53:35.900 --> 00:53:38.980
[Guest]: you have to be accommodated of the opposition.

00:53:38.980 --> 00:53:45.860
[Guest]: So we create a secular state, but we allow in our directive principles, that we will

00:53:45.860 --> 00:53:53.780
[Guest]: think about UCC, we will think about religious conversion, we will allow, we'll think about

00:53:53.780 --> 00:53:57.420
[Guest]: what to do with animal husbandry and cow slaughter, right?

00:53:57.420 --> 00:54:03.980
[Guest]: So in some ways, and many, many have pointed out, it has become a practice that anything,

00:54:03.980 --> 00:54:10.340
[Guest]: any government functions in India happens through a Hindu ritual.

00:54:10.340 --> 00:54:17.820
[Guest]: Now, you could say that this is a cultural practice, but then by following one sort of

00:54:17.820 --> 00:54:25.460
[Guest]: cultural practice, you're basically towing to the majoritarian ritual practice.

00:54:25.460 --> 00:54:32.820
[Guest]: So I think that's the reflection of the ideological conflict, as well as some scholars have gone

00:54:32.820 --> 00:54:38.740
[Guest]: to the extent of saying that what emerged in 1950s was a Hindu state.

00:54:38.740 --> 00:54:49.860
[Guest]: That basically, we were more accommodative of Hindu majoritarian demands than basically

00:54:49.860 --> 00:54:50.860
[Amit Varma]: liberal secular.

00:54:50.860 --> 00:54:55.340
[Amit Varma]: But the point that the BJP has throughout made, the Jansangh made before it and the

00:54:55.340 --> 00:55:01.420
[Amit Varma]: BJP has kind of made is that the Congress's version of secularism, what they call pseudo-secularism

00:55:01.420 --> 00:55:04.580
[Amit Varma]: was pandering to minorities.

00:55:04.580 --> 00:55:10.580
[Guest]: So I think perhaps in practice, Congress ended up doing that.

00:55:10.580 --> 00:55:18.780
[Guest]: So secularism, which was a matter of conviction of our founding fathers, because the idea

00:55:18.780 --> 00:55:26.100
[Guest]: of India would not have survived without a secular India, slowly became a politics of

00:55:26.100 --> 00:55:29.300
[Guest]: convenience, a politics of compulsion.

00:55:29.300 --> 00:55:35.740
[Guest]: But it's no longer a matter of sort of like ideological conviction, but basically, and

00:55:35.740 --> 00:55:42.940
[Guest]: I think BJP's opposition is that they do sort of appeasement of Muslims and they haven't

00:55:42.940 --> 00:55:45.940
[Guest]: done anything to uplift those population.

00:55:45.940 --> 00:55:49.500
[Guest]: And I think to some extent, that charge is not wrong.

00:55:49.500 --> 00:55:57.700
[Guest]: What the secular or so-called secular parties did, they basically sort of like used Muslim

00:55:57.700 --> 00:56:03.580
[Guest]: elites to mobilize Muslim population, but did not do enough for the Muslim masses in

00:56:03.580 --> 00:56:04.700
[Guest]: that sense.

00:56:04.700 --> 00:56:07.740
[Guest]: And come to think of it, right?

00:56:07.740 --> 00:56:13.180
[Guest]: In 60 years, Congress ruled most of the states.

00:56:13.180 --> 00:56:20.340
[Guest]: How many Muslim chief ministers can you think outside the state of Assam and Jammu Kashmir,

00:56:20.340 --> 00:56:26.100
[Guest]: where given the population, you will have a natural choice as a Muslim chief minister?

00:56:26.100 --> 00:56:34.540
[Guest]: I can remember only perhaps one example from Maharashtra and six month period for, I don't

00:56:34.540 --> 00:56:37.020
[Guest]: remember the name, but in Bihar, right?

00:56:37.020 --> 00:56:40.340
[Guest]: Other state Congress never made Muslim chief ministers.

00:56:40.340 --> 00:56:47.460
[Guest]: How many sort of like Muslim ministers or MPs came out from the Congress party or other

00:56:47.460 --> 00:56:48.460
[Guest]: secular parties?

00:56:48.460 --> 00:56:56.000
[Guest]: So the BJP is being now able to mobilize not just on the question of secularism, but also

00:56:56.000 --> 00:56:58.780
[Guest]: on the question of social justice, right?

00:56:58.780 --> 00:57:03.220
[Guest]: Because what they have managed to convince the last section of Indian population, that

00:57:03.220 --> 00:57:08.940
[Guest]: again, this was basically, so politics of reservation for OBC was not an OBC politics.

00:57:08.940 --> 00:57:11.940
[Guest]: It was just for Yadavs in North India, right?

00:57:11.940 --> 00:57:15.780
[Guest]: Politics reservation for Dalits was not meant for all SCs.

00:57:15.780 --> 00:57:19.500
[Guest]: It was just meant for Jatavs in Hindi heartland.

00:57:19.500 --> 00:57:27.020
[Guest]: And I think what BJP has managed to do is exploit the fault lines on both the social

00:57:27.020 --> 00:57:32.620
[Guest]: justice secularism, as well as some sort of like nationalism, patriotism angle.

