[Amit Varma]: Welcome back to The Scene and The Unseen.

00:59:50.100 --> 00:59:54.900
[Amit Varma]: I'm chatting with Rahul Verma, co-author with Prateep Chhibber of the excellent, thought-provoking

00:59:54.900 --> 00:59:56.860
[Amit Varma]: book Ideology and Identity.

00:59:56.860 --> 01:00:01.620
[Amit Varma]: It'll give you new insights into Indian politics, so do pick it up.

01:00:01.620 --> 01:00:06.100
[Amit Varma]: Continuing from where we left, you kind of described how you guys disagree with the notion

01:00:06.100 --> 01:00:08.420
[Amit Varma]: that Indian politics isn't ideological.

01:00:08.420 --> 01:00:13.460
[Amit Varma]: You pointed out that what we think of as a typical ideological cleavages of the West

01:00:13.460 --> 01:00:17.940
[Amit Varma]: don't apply to India, but we have our own ideological cleavages which have come from

01:00:17.940 --> 01:00:18.940
[Amit Varma]: our history.

01:00:18.940 --> 01:00:23.860
[Amit Varma]: One, around statism, the role of the state in redesigning society or the economy.

01:00:23.860 --> 01:00:26.700
[Amit Varma]: And two, around the politics of recognition.

01:00:26.700 --> 01:00:34.260
[Amit Varma]: Now, what you also do in your book is that you tackle people's descriptions of what Indian

01:00:34.260 --> 01:00:36.140
[Amit Varma]: politics actually is about.

01:00:36.140 --> 01:00:41.860
[Amit Varma]: For example, people say Indian politics is all identity politics based around vote banks.

01:00:41.860 --> 01:00:46.540
[Amit Varma]: People say it's patronage politics and voters are basically bribed during elections and

01:00:46.540 --> 01:00:47.540
[Amit Varma]: so on and so forth.

01:00:47.540 --> 01:00:49.300
[Amit Varma]: So tackle them one by one for me.

01:00:49.300 --> 01:00:54.500
[Amit Varma]: As far as identity politics is concerned, you're obviously not taking an absolute disposition

01:00:54.500 --> 01:00:58.540
[Amit Varma]: that identity doesn't matter because the title of your book is Ideology and Identity.

01:00:58.540 --> 01:01:02.740
[Amit Varma]: But tell me a little bit about your thinking on this and how do you test for the importance

01:01:02.740 --> 01:01:06.620
[Amit Varma]: of identity in the views that people hold?

01:01:06.620 --> 01:01:07.620
[Guest]: Okay.

01:01:07.620 --> 01:01:14.020
[Guest]: So, as you rightly said, we're not sort of taking that position that identities don't

01:01:14.020 --> 01:01:15.020
[Guest]: matter.

01:01:15.020 --> 01:01:23.900
[Guest]: In fact, one part of me deeply believes that your ideological position are also related

01:01:23.900 --> 01:01:32.940
[Guest]: to your social identities because given that the ideological conflict is on the question

01:01:32.940 --> 01:01:39.380
[Guest]: of identity, right, if it's about accommodating lower caste or religious minorities into

01:01:39.380 --> 01:01:43.540
[Guest]: body politics, then it is related to your identity.

01:01:43.540 --> 01:01:48.900
[Guest]: Similarly, your identity is determined in what kind of social and economic norms you

01:01:48.900 --> 01:01:54.160
[Guest]: are embedded in and if state is going to change that, then again, you are sort of like interacting

01:01:54.160 --> 01:01:57.020
[Guest]: with the identity portion.

01:01:57.020 --> 01:02:02.060
[Guest]: What we sort of like disagree with that there is some sort of like determinism attached

01:02:02.060 --> 01:02:10.180
[Guest]: to your identities as if identities alone determine what you are going to sort of like

01:02:10.180 --> 01:02:15.740
[Guest]: your policy preferences are going to be and which political party you're going to vote

01:02:15.740 --> 01:02:22.220
[Guest]: for and these kind of like debates or talks become much more common during elections in

01:02:22.220 --> 01:02:29.620
[Guest]: India where all conversations start and begins with caste as if you are born into a certain

01:02:29.620 --> 01:02:37.140
[Guest]: caste and you are going to vote for a particular political party and the way politics in India

01:02:37.140 --> 01:02:42.140
[Guest]: is changing, I think it is leaving many more people surprised because we started with that

01:02:42.140 --> 01:02:43.140
[Guest]: assumption.

01:02:43.140 --> 01:02:50.540
[Guest]: So, what we are basically doing in one of the chapters trying to sort of distangle identity

01:02:50.540 --> 01:02:56.980
[Guest]: and ideological platform and so in the world I come from where I was doing my PhD, there's

01:02:56.980 --> 01:03:02.700
[Guest]: a particular way of sort of like writing things, so you make a theoretical point, you also

01:03:02.700 --> 01:03:07.860
[Guest]: take on the counter arguments and then you provide evidence for your theoretical point

01:03:07.860 --> 01:03:14.100
[Guest]: and then there are new methods being developed to test for some of these questions.

01:03:14.100 --> 01:03:18.380
[Guest]: So how do you separate identity and ideology that was the question for us.

01:03:18.380 --> 01:03:25.380
[Guest]: So what we basically do in that chapter use evidence from a survey experiment to show

01:03:25.380 --> 01:03:32.940
[Guest]: that despite your identity, whatever caste or religion you are born into or practice,

01:03:32.940 --> 01:03:37.740
[Guest]: it doesn't, though it may be correlated with your ideological platform, but it is not deterministic

01:03:37.740 --> 01:03:38.740
[Guest]: in that sense.

01:03:38.740 --> 01:03:44.980
[Guest]: So that's what we do is basically showing that prejudice does play a role, but there

01:03:44.980 --> 01:03:50.140
[Guest]: is an independent effect of your ideological beliefs on what you sort of do.

01:03:50.140 --> 01:03:53.940
[Amit Varma]: So I have two kind of questions here.

01:03:53.940 --> 01:03:59.500
[Amit Varma]: One is that while it's obviously correct to say that identity is not deterministic and

01:03:59.500 --> 01:04:03.300
[Amit Varma]: you might even be arguing with a straw man there because who says it is, but while it's

01:04:03.300 --> 01:04:08.380
[Amit Varma]: correct to say that identity is not deterministic, like you can't look at an individual and say

01:04:08.380 --> 01:04:13.540
[Amit Varma]: that his identity or her identity determines the way she will vote.

01:04:13.540 --> 01:04:18.180
[Amit Varma]: But you can look at a group and say that it is likely that this group will feel this way

01:04:18.180 --> 01:04:19.900
[Amit Varma]: because of his identity.

01:04:19.900 --> 01:04:25.200
[Amit Varma]: An example being that I think it's fair to say and correct me if I'm wrong, that the

01:04:25.200 --> 01:04:30.020
[Amit Varma]: average upper caste person would be against reservations, or the average middle class

01:04:30.020 --> 01:04:33.460
[Amit Varma]: person would be against redistribution or high taxation.

01:04:33.460 --> 01:04:37.740
[Amit Varma]: And I'm not going into the merits of any of these policies, that they are more complicated.

01:04:37.740 --> 01:04:41.700
[Amit Varma]: But these are sort of the positions that they would hold on average.

01:04:41.700 --> 01:04:46.500
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, there is something to be said about identity, determining even one's ideological

01:04:46.500 --> 01:04:50.340
[Amit Varma]: position, which brings me to the second point, where you've got these very interesting surveys

01:04:50.340 --> 01:04:55.340
[Amit Varma]: in your books, and you've got a lot of data which shows that people's positions on certain

01:04:55.340 --> 01:05:01.820
[Amit Varma]: issues like reservations could be partly determined by identity, but are partly also determined

01:05:01.820 --> 01:05:06.180
[Amit Varma]: by ideological position or other first principles which they come from.

01:05:06.180 --> 01:05:12.940
[Amit Varma]: But my sort of how I teased that out is by asking you that, could it not be the case

01:05:12.940 --> 01:05:18.420
[Amit Varma]: that many of those counter views, many of those ideological positions that appear to

01:05:18.420 --> 01:05:23.820
[Amit Varma]: come from first principles, are rationalizations of a tribal instinct that they feel arising

01:05:23.820 --> 01:05:28.200
[Amit Varma]: from their identity, like how can you, you know, account for that?

01:05:28.200 --> 01:05:36.300
[Guest]: So you're right, I think that deterministic point was a bit far fetched, or a stretch.

01:05:36.300 --> 01:05:41.820
[Guest]: But think of what you said, all political parties are rooted in social cleavages, not

01:05:41.820 --> 01:05:44.880
[Guest]: just in India, across the world, right?

01:05:44.880 --> 01:05:49.160
[Guest]: If you look at Democrats in United States, a large portion of their votes would come

01:05:49.160 --> 01:05:54.660
[Guest]: from African Americans and white poor and Hispanics and immigrants.

01:05:54.660 --> 01:05:58.900
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, the argument can be made, in fact, I'm just thinking a lot, sorry for interrupting,

01:05:58.900 --> 01:06:04.540
[Amit Varma]: but the idea can also be made that a lot of that politics is actually more based on identity

01:06:04.540 --> 01:06:08.380
[Amit Varma]: than people previously would realize and less based on ideology.

01:06:08.380 --> 01:06:13.300
[Amit Varma]: And again, I'm just thinking aloud that could possibly account for the rightward drift of

01:06:13.300 --> 01:06:19.480
[Amit Varma]: the Republican Party in recent times, where a lot of the previously avowed ideological

01:06:19.480 --> 01:06:25.020
[Amit Varma]: principles like earlier, ideologically, they were for free trade, but now they no longer

01:06:25.020 --> 01:06:26.820
[Amit Varma]: seem to be so as they're all behind Trump.

01:06:26.820 --> 01:06:31.580
[Amit Varma]: So you could argue that a lot of those ideological positions were positions of convenience.

01:06:31.580 --> 01:06:34.700
[Amit Varma]: And it all boils down to identity at the end of the day.

01:06:34.700 --> 01:06:40.420
[Guest]: So the two, in fact, three questions, so let me tackle first two.

01:06:40.420 --> 01:06:46.100
[Guest]: So yes, there is a relationship between identity and voting for a particular party.

01:06:46.100 --> 01:06:48.700
[Guest]: But why are they doing so?

01:06:48.700 --> 01:06:53.860
[Guest]: Because that particular political party espouses some policy platforms that are closer to their

01:06:53.860 --> 01:06:55.180
[Guest]: identity.

01:06:55.180 --> 01:06:59.940
[Guest]: And those policy platforms are actually those ideological beliefs, right?

01:06:59.940 --> 01:07:03.860
[Guest]: Why does a Dalit vote for a Bahujan Samaj Party in Uttar Pradesh?

01:07:03.860 --> 01:07:08.560
[Guest]: Because they think that Bahujan Samaj Party takes care of Dalit interest, right?

01:07:08.560 --> 01:07:10.280
[Guest]: And that's the idea.

01:07:10.280 --> 01:07:16.860
[Guest]: This is so when I was talking about the determinism, it is not because I was born into this category

01:07:16.860 --> 01:07:23.260
[Guest]: and I have a leader belongs to that category and we like each other is basically because

01:07:23.260 --> 01:07:28.380
[Guest]: I think that this party takes care of my interest.

01:07:28.380 --> 01:07:34.840
[Guest]: And interests are basically reflected in your ideological leanings, right?

01:07:34.840 --> 01:07:38.200
[Guest]: So that's the limited point I was trying to make there.

01:07:38.200 --> 01:07:45.340
[Guest]: The second, I think what you are trying to suggest is that parties leave their position

01:07:45.340 --> 01:07:48.740
[Guest]: and they sort of take up new positions.

01:07:48.740 --> 01:07:51.220
[Guest]: So it's a matter of convenience.

01:07:51.220 --> 01:07:56.900
[Guest]: You can say that, but then this ideological space, which is structures or under grits

01:07:56.900 --> 01:08:02.020
[Guest]: the conflict and party politics is not a static space.

01:08:02.020 --> 01:08:07.820
[Guest]: Political parties in some ways, organizationally dynamic, they will keep bringing new voters

01:08:07.820 --> 01:08:09.640
[Guest]: leaving out some old voters.

01:08:09.640 --> 01:08:14.320
[Guest]: And that's why the ideological space, not just because of the time and space, but because

01:08:14.320 --> 01:08:20.740
[Guest]: of the groups that you sort of like take into that ideological space will also keep moving.

01:08:20.740 --> 01:08:24.060
[Guest]: And sometimes it is moved by that's the third point.

01:08:24.060 --> 01:08:26.860
[Guest]: It is moved by leaders, right?

01:08:26.860 --> 01:08:31.300
[Guest]: And that's one of the chapters where we talk about people are not attached to leaders because

01:08:31.300 --> 01:08:38.860
[Guest]: they just like the leader because leaders basically represent a kind of sort of become

01:08:38.860 --> 01:08:44.780
[Guest]: a heuristic or a hint for the ideological platforms they want to sort of like believe

01:08:44.780 --> 01:08:45.780
[Guest]: in.

01:08:45.780 --> 01:08:53.420
[Guest]: And I think one of the points which you were sort of bringing up and it's a hard question

01:08:53.420 --> 01:09:00.500
[Guest]: to answer is basically whether they like the leader and then decide the platform, which

01:09:00.500 --> 01:09:08.180
[Guest]: you were mentioning in the case of political party and identities, or they have a policy

01:09:08.180 --> 01:09:11.660
[Guest]: platform and then they find the leader closest to that policy platform.

01:09:11.660 --> 01:09:16.460
[Amit Varma]: What is not so much leader and policy platform like another contestation I had, you know,

01:09:16.460 --> 01:09:22.020
[Amit Varma]: in your book where at some point you seem to imply that, like in terms of statism, obviously,

01:09:22.020 --> 01:09:28.020
[Amit Varma]: I totally agree with you about the statism cleavage that exists around the state remaking

01:09:28.020 --> 01:09:29.020
[Amit Varma]: society.

01:09:29.020 --> 01:09:33.740
[Amit Varma]: But as far as the state remaking the economy is concerned, I think there are very, very,

01:09:33.740 --> 01:09:38.220
[Amit Varma]: very few people like me, who would want the state to not interfere with the economy and

01:09:38.220 --> 01:09:40.340
[Amit Varma]: would allow markets to play a hand.

01:09:40.340 --> 01:09:45.100
[Amit Varma]: And I think that a lot of the people in 2014, who supported Modi, some of them were taken

01:09:45.100 --> 01:09:51.500
[Amit Varma]: in by the rhetoric, but a lot of them were perhaps couching their innate preference for

01:09:51.500 --> 01:09:56.500
[Amit Varma]: some of the other positions of the BJP, like their positions on Muslims or cow slaughter

01:09:56.500 --> 01:10:01.860
[Amit Varma]: or whatever, and instead making it sound respectable by talking about economic freedoms, where

01:10:01.860 --> 01:10:04.380
[Amit Varma]: they didn't really give a damn about economic freedoms.

01:10:04.380 --> 01:10:11.260
[Amit Varma]: So it's not that they decide to support a particular leader, but it's like, okay, I

01:10:11.260 --> 01:10:13.780
[Amit Varma]: do not like Muslims, but I cannot say that.

01:10:13.780 --> 01:10:16.860
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, I will say that I want free markets.

01:10:16.860 --> 01:10:17.860
[Amit Varma]: Yeah.

01:10:17.860 --> 01:10:18.860
[Guest]: Yeah.

01:10:18.860 --> 01:10:21.260
[Guest]: But that's the way.

01:10:21.260 --> 01:10:25.900
[Amit Varma]: So what you say is identity couched as ideology.

01:10:25.900 --> 01:10:33.260
[Guest]: So on the question of majoritarianism, no, but you are expressing so you're not saying,

01:10:33.260 --> 01:10:41.020
[Guest]: but by voting for that particular political party, it may not be your top priority, right?

01:10:41.020 --> 01:10:45.500
[Guest]: So you may be actually so that's a very different thing, what you're saying that you're voting

01:10:45.500 --> 01:10:51.460
[Guest]: for that particular political party, which espouses anti Muslim view, and you have voted

01:10:51.460 --> 01:10:57.260
[Guest]: for the anti Muslim view, but you don't want to say that out loud, right?

01:10:57.260 --> 01:11:02.900
[Guest]: And so you're saying it's it's, but but is being anti Muslim?

01:11:02.900 --> 01:11:06.300
[Guest]: Why are you being is it just prejudice against Muslims?

01:11:06.300 --> 01:11:12.340
[Guest]: Or do you think you have problems with Muslims because there are some interesting while they

01:11:12.340 --> 01:11:16.620
[Guest]: are taking away your resources that given more preference by the government?

01:11:16.620 --> 01:11:18.140
[Guest]: Why do you not like Muslims?

01:11:18.140 --> 01:11:23.740
[Amit Varma]: I am saying that there are perhaps a substantial number of people who are simply bigoted, and

01:11:23.740 --> 01:11:27.020
[Amit Varma]: who couch their bigotry in more respectable terms.

01:11:27.020 --> 01:11:30.620
[Amit Varma]: So they will find a way to couch like they will rail against the pseudo secularism of

01:11:30.620 --> 01:11:34.140
[Amit Varma]: the Congress, which is actually a point with a lot of merit.

01:11:34.140 --> 01:11:37.980
[Amit Varma]: But they might be bringing that point up for other reasons.

01:11:37.980 --> 01:11:42.740
[Amit Varma]: Or they might be saying that no, you know, we need minimum government maximum governance,

01:11:42.740 --> 01:11:47.020
[Amit Varma]: which of course, in reality hasn't happened at all under Modi, we've had maximum governance,

01:11:47.020 --> 01:11:48.900
[Amit Varma]: maximum governance.

01:11:48.900 --> 01:11:53.420
[Amit Varma]: But you know, they will couch it in respectable ideological terms.

01:11:53.420 --> 01:11:56.140
[Amit Varma]: But those instincts will be based around identity.

01:11:56.140 --> 01:12:01.140
[Guest]: I'm just I mean, I don't mean to disagree with no, no, no, I think what you're asking

01:12:01.140 --> 01:12:02.900
[Guest]: is a very, very important question.

01:12:02.900 --> 01:12:06.460
[Guest]: We don't do justice to that question in the book.

01:12:06.460 --> 01:12:10.420
[Guest]: And perhaps this is something to sort of like, think about.

01:12:10.420 --> 01:12:16.740
[Guest]: Because if your hypothesis about prevalence of bigotry is correct, that we have high prevalence

01:12:16.740 --> 01:12:22.300
[Guest]: of bigotry, the implications of that is that we should be seeing riots or communal violence

01:12:22.300 --> 01:12:23.980
[Guest]: almost on daily basis.

01:12:23.980 --> 01:12:29.580
[Guest]: We don't see that happening, I think, or then you would argue that bigotry to violence is

01:12:29.580 --> 01:12:32.580
[Guest]: sort of like another chain.

01:12:32.580 --> 01:12:33.580
[Amit Varma]: It's another chain.

01:12:33.580 --> 01:12:36.900
[Amit Varma]: But also, I'm not saying there's a high prevalence of bigotry, I kind of have more faith in my

01:12:36.900 --> 01:12:37.900
[Amit Varma]: country than that.

01:12:37.900 --> 01:12:43.460
[Amit Varma]: I think that there are a lot of reasons why one can vote for, say, the BJP and bigotry

01:12:43.460 --> 01:12:45.020
[Amit Varma]: is just one small part of the mix.

01:12:45.020 --> 01:12:49.460
[Guest]: I think what you're asking is, yeah.

01:12:49.460 --> 01:12:54.100
[Amit Varma]: And also, I completely like we'll talk about leadership a little later in the episode.

01:12:54.100 --> 01:13:00.100
[Amit Varma]: But I also agree that, you know, Modi as a transformational leader, a lot of his support,

01:13:00.100 --> 01:13:04.300
[Amit Varma]: especially in these recent elections, when you consider the broad base of the support,

01:13:04.300 --> 01:13:08.340
[Amit Varma]: and the number of Dalits who voted for Modi, a lot of it is not because of identity is

01:13:08.340 --> 01:13:09.820
[Amit Varma]: definitely because of ideology.

01:13:09.820 --> 01:13:14.060
[Amit Varma]: And that almost, in fact, proves very emphatically the point that you're making.

01:13:14.060 --> 01:13:18.940
[Amit Varma]: So I didn't really mean to sound as if I like that.

01:13:18.940 --> 01:13:19.940
[Guest]: I like those questions.

01:13:19.940 --> 01:13:25.460
[Guest]: In fact, some pushback is very, very important, because this is not the end of the research

01:13:25.460 --> 01:13:28.780
[Guest]: on ideology and party system, this is the beginning of it.

01:13:28.780 --> 01:13:33.580
[Guest]: And of course, the beginning of the research, there are going to be lots of mistakes, there

01:13:33.580 --> 01:13:38.100
[Guest]: are a lot of going to be deficiencies, and these questions will make us think hard and

01:13:38.100 --> 01:13:39.580
[Amit Varma]: perhaps come up with better answers.

01:13:39.580 --> 01:13:44.620
[Amit Varma]: No, and you've made me through your book, you guys have made me question my prior assumptions.

01:13:44.620 --> 01:13:49.380
[Amit Varma]: So in a sense, maybe this is just reflexive, I'm fighting back.

01:13:49.380 --> 01:13:53.900
[Amit Varma]: Another point that you kind of bring up, and again, you're not taking an absolute disposition,

01:13:53.900 --> 01:13:59.380
[Amit Varma]: it's important to say is, for example, voter bribery, right, where you say that it is simplistic

01:13:59.380 --> 01:14:03.500
[Amit Varma]: to say that voters are bribed during elections, that's not quite how it is.

01:14:03.500 --> 01:14:05.900
[Amit Varma]: Can you elaborate on that?

01:14:05.900 --> 01:14:12.500
[Guest]: So now there is a large literature on developing countries, which basically describes them,

01:14:12.500 --> 01:14:18.740
[Guest]: these countries as patronage democracies, clientelistic politics, where basically the

01:14:18.740 --> 01:14:25.420
[Guest]: one line summary of this argument is that voters in these countries vote for a politician

01:14:25.420 --> 01:14:33.300
[Guest]: in exchange of some goodies that could range from job expectation of job to a sari, a samosa,

01:14:33.300 --> 01:14:35.380
[Guest]: or some cash.

01:14:35.380 --> 01:14:42.900
[Guest]: Now, we're not saying that these things are not there in our elections, basically, that

01:14:42.900 --> 01:14:47.220
[Guest]: would mean we're closing eyes and not looking at what is happening.

01:14:47.220 --> 01:14:53.660
[Guest]: And so all of this, like cash supply or distribution of these goodies are there.

01:14:53.660 --> 01:15:00.540
[Guest]: But what we are sort of challenging is that the vote is not contingent upon whether I

01:15:00.540 --> 01:15:03.100
[Guest]: receive an item or not.

01:15:03.100 --> 01:15:10.940
[Guest]: It has become like, so it's not quid pro quo, but it's anti-quid pro quo, where basically

01:15:10.940 --> 01:15:17.220
[Guest]: like a poker game, the political culture, and this is not a good thing, in last 70 years

01:15:17.220 --> 01:15:25.140
[Guest]: have evolved in a way that all politicians have to put in money, and that will sort of

01:15:25.140 --> 01:15:30.300
[Guest]: like make them seem winnable or competitive to be in the race.

01:15:30.300 --> 01:15:35.180
[Guest]: But that would not sort of determine whether they are going to win the election for sure

01:15:35.180 --> 01:15:36.180
[Guest]: or not.

01:15:36.180 --> 01:15:38.020
[Amit Varma]: But if you don't put in money, you're surely going to lose.

01:15:38.020 --> 01:15:39.020
[Amit Varma]: So it's like a hygiene factor.

01:15:39.020 --> 01:15:42.860
[Amit Varma]: I think our mutual friend Milan Vaishnav, who in fact introduced us, made this point

01:15:42.860 --> 01:15:47.260
[Amit Varma]: in his podcast with me where he kind of said that, you know, whether bribery works or not,

01:15:47.260 --> 01:15:54.180
[Amit Varma]: all parties have to at least offer a bribe and a counterpoint to doesn't that then make

01:15:54.180 --> 01:15:58.220
[Amit Varma]: bribery the rigor, for example, and it also depends on like bribery is not just giving

01:15:58.220 --> 01:16:02.660
[Amit Varma]: a sack of rice or a pressure cooker or whatever, there are sort of policy bribes, for example,

01:16:02.660 --> 01:16:07.220
[Amit Varma]: farm loan waivers, we've kind of reached the equilibrium in this country where it is understood

01:16:07.220 --> 01:16:11.220
[Amit Varma]: that to win an election, that is one of the things you will have to do offer a farm loan

01:16:11.220 --> 01:16:16.940
[Amit Varma]: waiver, which often in the short immediate term, I think provides even a necessary anesthetic

01:16:16.940 --> 01:16:20.460
[Amit Varma]: for farmers sometimes, but is nowhere near the long term solution that we need to do

01:16:20.460 --> 01:16:23.180
[Amit Varma]: and we don't carry out those long term structural reforms.

01:16:23.180 --> 01:16:29.380
[Guest]: Absolutely, I completely agree with you. And that's why we think that despite this ideological

01:16:29.380 --> 01:16:36.780
[Guest]: conflict, the political culture is such that competitive populism in our politics is going

01:16:36.780 --> 01:16:43.060
[Guest]: to continue. And, and the limited point we wanted to sort of make through this chapter

01:16:43.060 --> 01:16:53.900
[Guest]: is that these goodies or even bribery by the incumbent in form of policy happens during

01:16:53.900 --> 01:16:59.680
[Guest]: all party regimes. And if this was driving our electoral politics, incumbents would always

01:16:59.680 --> 01:17:05.060
[Guest]: have a leg up. And they should be returning back not just as MPs, MLAs and government

01:17:05.060 --> 01:17:13.620
[Guest]: leaders. Like we have a big example on 2017 UP election, where Akhilesh Yadav ran a government

01:17:13.620 --> 01:17:19.860
[Guest]: which was patronage by rule book. In fact, targeted almost every kind of voter that was

01:17:19.860 --> 01:17:26.940
[Guest]: possible. And Akhilesh by no means was running. So his government may have been a little bit

01:17:26.940 --> 01:17:33.060
[Guest]: unpopular, but he was certainly seen as a popular leader. And despite that, they not

01:17:33.060 --> 01:17:40.020
[Guest]: just lost the elections, but lost it badly. So the limited idea we are making, there is

01:17:40.020 --> 01:17:47.260
[Guest]: influence of the so these goodies are very much part of our election game. A lot of cash

01:17:47.260 --> 01:17:52.300
[Guest]: is sort of like needed to build a campaign in a short period of time. But the vote is

01:17:52.300 --> 01:17:59.500
[Guest]: not contingent upon this vote is very much an independent choice. It is partly driven

01:17:59.500 --> 01:18:07.140
[Guest]: by identity, partly driven by ideology. Maybe at margins, some votes will be getting influenced

01:18:07.140 --> 01:18:13.620
[Guest]: by these goodies and welfare policies. But to describe this as a patronage democracy

01:18:13.620 --> 01:18:18.780
[Guest]: or a clientelistic politics is a little bit of a stretch.

01:18:18.780 --> 01:18:22.060
[Amit Varma]: That's a fair point. And you're making a nuanced point, you're not being absolutist in saying

01:18:22.060 --> 01:18:25.360
[Amit Varma]: that bribery doesn't matter at all you're saying is multifactorial. This might be one

01:18:25.360 --> 01:18:30.300
[Amit Varma]: of the factors. Let's not overstate it. Just to needle you, I say I used to write weekly

01:18:30.300 --> 01:18:34.420
[Amit Varma]: limericks for the Times of India. So just to needle you, I'll quote a limerick about

01:18:34.420 --> 01:18:39.940
[Amit Varma]: exactly the subject. I think it's called politics and the limerick is a neta who loves currency

01:18:39.940 --> 01:18:45.740
[Amit Varma]: notes told me what his line of work denotes. It is kind of funny. We steal people's money

01:18:45.740 --> 01:18:51.940
[Amit Varma]: and use some of it to buy their votes. Stop good. No, but your book is perhaps a response

01:18:51.940 --> 01:18:56.820
[Amit Varma]: to that. Let's move on to another subject which you know, you brought up a moment ago

01:18:56.820 --> 01:19:02.860
[Amit Varma]: and I found your chapter on it quite fascinating, which is the subject of leadership, where

01:19:02.860 --> 01:19:07.980
[Amit Varma]: you point out that there are really two kinds of leaders in politics, especially Indian

01:19:07.980 --> 01:19:13.860
[Amit Varma]: politics. And one kind is driven by ideology. Tell me a little bit more about this.

01:19:13.860 --> 01:19:20.940
[Guest]: So and it's related to this logic of bribery and patronage. So a lot of research in political

01:19:20.940 --> 01:19:30.500
[Guest]: science is basically focused on these small time fixers or very local level politicians

01:19:30.500 --> 01:19:37.820
[Guest]: whom we describe as transactional leaders that I will do something for you and you vote

01:19:37.820 --> 01:19:45.540
[Guest]: for me. And and so the focus has been on these fixers and brokers and local level politicians.

01:19:45.540 --> 01:19:51.100
[Guest]: But political science, and this is like a serious problem within political science that

01:19:51.100 --> 01:19:57.540
[Guest]: we don't study leaders, leaders of sort of like, not just prime ministers or chief ministers,

01:19:57.540 --> 01:20:04.700
[Guest]: but basically people who have influence in a large part of society. And the reason they

01:20:04.700 --> 01:20:11.460
[Guest]: have a large influence, because they project themselves as transformational, they may not

01:20:11.460 --> 01:20:16.660
[Guest]: turn out to be transformational. But the vision they project is that they are going to transform

01:20:16.660 --> 01:20:24.580
[Guest]: society. And because of that kind of vision, they can not only enthuse their own party

01:20:24.580 --> 01:20:32.500
[Guest]: carders, but they inspire a large swathe of masses. And there is some measurable impacts,

01:20:32.500 --> 01:20:38.860
[Guest]: which we show in the book. But think of the politics in this country is not shaped by

01:20:38.860 --> 01:20:44.260
[Guest]: these local level brokers and local level politicians. Political parties are moved in

01:20:44.260 --> 01:20:51.940
[Guest]: moved in the system by these big influential leaders. As soon as you think of Lalu Yadav,

01:20:51.940 --> 01:20:58.500
[Guest]: you may sort of like imagine something about him of being a backward caste politician,

01:20:58.500 --> 01:21:05.020
[Guest]: right? Mayawati, a Dalit politician, or Narendra Modi, a Hindu Hudayshamrat, you attach some

01:21:05.020 --> 01:21:11.140
[Guest]: ideas with all these leaders, right? And that's why what we are trying to make the case in

01:21:11.140 --> 01:21:18.780
[Guest]: this chapter is these leaders who project themselves as transformational, portray an

01:21:18.780 --> 01:21:25.140
[Guest]: ideological vision, and they structure or shape party politics in the country.

01:21:25.140 --> 01:21:28.780
[Amit Varma]: Sadanand And so transactional leaders tend to be more

01:21:28.780 --> 01:21:33.660
[Amit Varma]: local, whereas transformational leaders are, you know, many of the great names that have

01:21:33.660 --> 01:21:41.380
[Amit Varma]: walked on the Indian political landscape, like Indira Gandhi, Anna Durai, MG Ramchandran,

01:21:41.380 --> 01:21:47.180
[Amit Varma]: Narendra Modi, to the present day, Mayawati and Kanchi Ram are all transformational leaders,

01:21:47.180 --> 01:21:54.380
[Amit Varma]: because there is a broader ideological view that they have, and a specific place they

01:21:54.380 --> 01:22:00.420
[Amit Varma]: have on the issues of both statism and recognition that appeals to people.

01:22:00.420 --> 01:22:07.140
[Guest]: Yeah, and think of like, in 2014 and 2019, journalists and political scientists and common

01:22:07.140 --> 01:22:12.480
[Guest]: people alike would talk about a Modi effect in the election. What does Modi effect means?

01:22:12.480 --> 01:22:19.060
[Guest]: Is it just about Modi's personality? He was not promising them that you vote for me, I

01:22:19.060 --> 01:22:24.580
[Guest]: will get a road in next to your house, or I'll offer you a samosa or a sari or 500 rupee

01:22:24.580 --> 01:22:30.980
[Guest]: note, I might be offering 15 lakh that's different. But But the idea is the even when we talk

01:22:30.980 --> 01:22:37.460
[Guest]: about Narendra Modi, Narendra Modi represents some vision, and he can very well articulate

01:22:37.460 --> 01:22:43.620
[Guest]: that vision. And perhaps that is the reason of his popularity, because there is clarity

01:22:43.620 --> 01:22:48.660
[Guest]: of articulation on one side of the ideological spectrum, and there is disarray on the other

01:22:48.660 --> 01:22:54.700
[Guest]: side. And that increases the gap, which sort of like create some Modi effect.

01:22:54.700 --> 01:22:59.540
[Amit Varma]: No, and as I'll ask you to elaborate on as we're ending the episode a little later, will

01:22:59.540 --> 01:23:06.020
[Amit Varma]: be essentially how Modi's transformational appeal as it were, is so vast that he actually

01:23:06.020 --> 01:23:09.660
[Amit Varma]: I think in this election, more Dalits voted for the BJP than for Congress.

01:23:09.660 --> 01:23:11.860
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, that had happened in 2014.

01:23:11.860 --> 01:23:17.580
[Amit Varma]: In 2014 also. And in fact, the Dalit leader, Jignesh Mewani, had a lament on Twitter rather

01:23:17.580 --> 01:23:22.100
[Amit Varma]: about how he doesn't understand why so many Dalits are voting for the BJP. And given,

01:23:22.100 --> 01:23:25.580
[Amit Varma]: you know, where the BJP once stood on the politics of recognition is surprising, but

01:23:25.580 --> 01:23:30.260
[Amit Varma]: it's also very interesting how, you know, Modi's managed to on the basis of his leadership

01:23:30.260 --> 01:23:35.020
[Amit Varma]: sort of widen the base of his party as it were, what I'm going to ask you to do and

01:23:35.020 --> 01:23:40.860
[Amit Varma]: what I found very sort of insightful. And if I had one feedback for the book, I would

01:23:40.860 --> 01:23:45.660
[Amit Varma]: ask you, why did this come so late in the book, where you talk about the four different

01:23:45.660 --> 01:23:51.460
[Amit Varma]: political periods in the political evolution of India, which is really fascinating to me.

01:23:51.460 --> 01:23:53.780
[Amit Varma]: So just kind of take me through those four periods.

01:23:53.780 --> 01:23:58.780
[Guest]: Okay, so it comes late into the book, because we are boring political scientists, and we

01:23:58.780 --> 01:24:03.460
[Guest]: have sort of like a way of presenting the material, right? Theory, counter argument,

01:24:03.460 --> 01:24:06.900
[Guest]: evidence, and then what are the implications, right? What is the big picture implication

01:24:06.900 --> 01:24:13.660
[Guest]: of this? So, so that's the Dandamar way of writing things. So what we are basically it's

01:24:13.660 --> 01:24:19.620
[Guest]: a re-reading of Indian political history. So there is a consensus among political scientists

01:24:19.620 --> 01:24:28.420
[Guest]: that 1952 to 67 was the first phase of party system where Congress was a dominant party.

01:24:28.420 --> 01:24:32.660
[Guest]: Political scientists like me care about party system because it structures the rules of

01:24:32.660 --> 01:24:37.700
[Guest]: the competition. So in some ways, as a voter, you are going to choose from the menu that

01:24:37.700 --> 01:24:43.740
[Guest]: you are going to get. And so party system in some ways is presenting you the effective

01:24:43.740 --> 01:24:44.740
[Amit Varma]: choices that you have.

01:24:44.740 --> 01:24:48.040
[Amit Varma]: And what I found particularly interesting about your analysis was that you were talking

01:24:48.040 --> 01:24:52.460
[Amit Varma]: about these four different periods in the context of the ideological cleavages in your

01:24:52.460 --> 01:24:56.500
[Amit Varma]: book, which is statism and recognition. So kind of take me through that, that you know,

01:24:56.500 --> 01:25:00.500
[Amit Varma]: where was the Congress in that first period with regard to those two? How did that change?

01:25:00.500 --> 01:25:01.500
[Guest]: How did it evolve?

01:25:01.500 --> 01:25:09.220
[Guest]: Well, I would sort of like now ask you to imagine a three-dimensional space where if

01:25:09.220 --> 01:25:15.260
[Guest]: you have one axis of recognition and other axis of statism, Congress in the beginning

01:25:15.260 --> 01:25:21.740
[Guest]: is sort of sitting at the center, the large umbrella political party sitting at the center.

01:25:21.740 --> 01:25:27.500
[Guest]: Then on the right, you have lots of smaller political parties. So Bharatiya Jan Sangh,

01:25:27.500 --> 01:25:34.820
[Guest]: Ram Rajyam Parishad of Karpatri Maharaj, Hindu Mahasabha, later on in 60s, you get Swatantra

01:25:34.820 --> 01:25:41.300
[Guest]: Party. So there were lots of these parties. On the other side, you had lots of socialist

01:25:41.300 --> 01:25:47.340
[Guest]: parties. So Praja Socialist Party, Kishan Mazdoor Party, Communist Parties. So these

01:25:47.340 --> 01:25:53.300
[Guest]: were there in the beginning. What happens in 1967, dominance of Congress in the beginning,

01:25:53.300 --> 01:25:54.300
[Amit Varma]: Congress is sitting at the center.

01:25:54.300 --> 01:25:59.100
[Amit Varma]: Just to clarify, then the Congress is doing both a certain amount of statism and the politics

01:25:59.100 --> 01:26:03.220
[Amit Varma]: of recognition. But those on the left, the communists and the socialists and all feel

01:26:03.220 --> 01:26:04.220
[Amit Varma]: not enough.

01:26:04.220 --> 01:26:05.220
[Amit Varma]: Yes.

01:26:05.220 --> 01:26:08.820
[Amit Varma]: And those on the right say that no, the state should not interfere with society so much

01:26:08.820 --> 01:26:10.540
[Guest]: and no, don't give reservations.

01:26:10.540 --> 01:26:15.700
[Guest]: That is correct. So actually, the first split in the Congress, first big, so there was a

01:26:15.700 --> 01:26:27.100
[Guest]: split around 1906, when the Surat Congress got split. But I think in 1930s and 40s, when

01:26:27.100 --> 01:26:32.580
[Guest]: we are closer to the independence, there were politicians who you would describe as socialist

01:26:32.580 --> 01:26:37.740
[Guest]: or communist within the Congress Party. So Congress was the large national umbrella movement.

01:26:37.740 --> 01:26:44.420
[Guest]: The socialist wing of the Congress Party felt, and at one point Nehru was part of that group

01:26:44.420 --> 01:26:52.660
[Guest]: felt, that the Congress leadership is not doing enough on their policy platform. So

01:26:52.660 --> 01:26:58.140
[Guest]: they leave the Congress Party and form the Congress Socialist Party in 1934, which later

01:26:58.140 --> 01:27:04.180
[Guest]: on becomes the Praja Socialist Party and KMPP and then Socialist Party. So that's the linear.

01:27:04.180 --> 01:27:10.620
[Guest]: So what you would in traditional sense, think of the socialist within the Congress, left

01:27:10.620 --> 01:27:17.980
[Guest]: the Congress pre-independence and slowly, the process was complete by 1950s, 60s. And

01:27:17.980 --> 01:27:23.220
[Guest]: then you had lots of these right wing players. So Congress was basically sitting in the center

01:27:23.220 --> 01:27:28.540
[Guest]: in a sense, they were doing few things, but not doing enough. For example, they did appoint

01:27:28.540 --> 01:27:34.380
[Guest]: Kaka Kalelkar commission on the OBC reservation, but they didn't do anything on that. Right.

01:27:34.380 --> 01:27:42.780
[Guest]: And similarly on the Hindu code bill happens, but nothing happens on the uniform civil codes.

01:27:42.780 --> 01:27:48.180
[Guest]: So they were not taking it to the logical conclusion. And whereas the right wing parties

01:27:48.180 --> 01:27:54.740
[Guest]: had a very different idea. So in 67, when Mrs. Gandhi is now the prime minister of the

01:27:54.740 --> 01:28:02.740
[Guest]: country, she faces challenge from the right. And what she does is basically moves the Congress

01:28:02.740 --> 01:28:09.260
[Guest]: party closer to the council. In fact, the 67 government had a communist party of India,

01:28:09.260 --> 01:28:15.180
[Guest]: basically supporting Mrs. Gandhi's Congress. So she moves closer to those ideological position

01:28:15.180 --> 01:28:22.260
[Guest]: on both, especially the statism part between 67 and 89. In fact, she takes lots of steps

01:28:22.260 --> 01:28:29.740
[Guest]: related to the marriage age, related to dowry, which basically further in some ways, the

01:28:29.740 --> 01:28:35.500
[Guest]: traditionalist, the Hindu traditionalist within the Congress felt further marginalized, and

01:28:35.500 --> 01:28:40.300
[Guest]: they slowly started leaving out the Congress party. If you think of the, the syndicates

01:28:40.300 --> 01:28:45.820
[Guest]: within the Congress party, they were in some ways the conservative politicians. In fact,

01:28:45.820 --> 01:28:51.700
[Guest]: Gulzarilal Nanda, who was two time interim prime minister, is also one of the founding

01:28:51.700 --> 01:28:57.580
[Guest]: members of the Vishwa Hindu Parishad. So because she moves the Congress party in one direction,

01:28:57.580 --> 01:29:02.300
[Guest]: now the space was created there. So right leaning elements basically started coming

01:29:02.300 --> 01:29:09.340
[Guest]: together. So now, now what you see in 1980 as Bharatiya Janata Party is not just the

01:29:09.340 --> 01:29:14.380
[Guest]: Bharatiya Janata Party, it had elements of BJS, but also elements of Hindu Mahasabha,

01:29:14.380 --> 01:29:19.940
[Guest]: elements of Ram Rajya Parishad, elements of Swatantrata Party, elements of Congress organization,

01:29:19.940 --> 01:29:24.940
[Guest]: which was the split splinter group of the Congress party. So all the conservative elements

01:29:24.940 --> 01:29:31.380
[Guest]: basically coalesced together and form the Bharatiya Janata Party in 1980s. And if you

01:29:31.380 --> 01:29:37.500
[Guest]: think of the vote share with BJP is basically getting in 18991, this is basically the addition

01:29:37.500 --> 01:29:40.700
[Guest]: of all these groups in what they used to get in 1960s.

01:29:40.700 --> 01:29:45.300
[Amit Varma]: It's fascinating that for her personal political survival, Indira Gandhi needs to reposition

01:29:45.300 --> 01:29:50.400
[Amit Varma]: herself politically. And because her opponents in the party happen to be towards the right,

01:29:50.400 --> 01:29:55.300
[Amit Varma]: she goes towards left again, we are using western terms, but she goes towards the left,

01:29:55.300 --> 01:29:59.900
[Amit Varma]: there's more statism, therefore, she goes towards, and therefore, she leaves that space,

01:29:59.900 --> 01:30:05.340
[Amit Varma]: which eventually coalesces all those years later into the BJP, which is now a more powerful

01:30:05.340 --> 01:30:11.180
[Amit Varma]: force. And in fact, you point out, I think at one point that in the 89 or 91 elections,

01:30:11.180 --> 01:30:19.140
[Amit Varma]: the BJP got as the same vote share as the Jansan plus the Swatantra Party in the 60s.

01:30:19.140 --> 01:30:24.500
[Amit Varma]: So it actually coalesced into that one entity. And then that's correct. So in terms of the

01:30:24.500 --> 01:30:28.860
[Amit Varma]: ideological issues of statism and recognition, Indira Gandhi moved a lot towards statism

01:30:28.860 --> 01:30:31.080
[Guest]: and on the recognition front, what was happening?

01:30:31.080 --> 01:30:38.140
[Guest]: So recognition front, what happens is basically, she doesn't, she's standing right there, which

01:30:38.140 --> 01:30:45.300
[Guest]: basically now opens up a space for all these socialist parties. Basically, they were trying

01:30:45.300 --> 01:30:50.380
[Guest]: to do some sort of like class mobilization in the first party system. Post 67, they all

01:30:50.380 --> 01:30:55.260
[Guest]: become backward caste parties of North India. So they start because nothing was happening

01:30:55.260 --> 01:31:01.340
[Guest]: on the reservation front. So now basically, the centrist Congress Party is caught in the

01:31:01.340 --> 01:31:07.100
[Guest]: middle, you have basically socialist parties mobilizing on the caste angle, the right wing

01:31:07.100 --> 01:31:11.780
[Guest]: parties mobilizing on the religion angle, and the statism angle and the Communist Party

01:31:11.780 --> 01:31:18.020
[Guest]: saying you have not done enough on the statism. So basically, Congress starts getting squeezed.

01:31:18.020 --> 01:31:24.300
[Guest]: So in the second party system, which is 67 to 89, Congress though remains dominant nationally,

01:31:24.300 --> 01:31:29.020
[Guest]: but in the states now it is facing challenges in some places from the BJP in some places

01:31:29.020 --> 01:31:34.300
[Guest]: from the Communist in some places from the these backward caste parties or regional parties.

01:31:34.300 --> 01:31:38.420
[Amit Varma]: And everywhere these regional parties have come up like in Tamil Nadu, for example, GMK

01:31:38.420 --> 01:31:44.420
[Amit Varma]: basically, yeah, running the roost, then let's go to the third party. So third party system

01:31:44.420 --> 01:31:50.860
[Guest]: basically begins in 1989, when Congress loses its national dominance also, and we get a

01:31:50.860 --> 01:31:56.820
[Guest]: fragmented party system. So what happens in this period, that in places where Congress

01:31:56.820 --> 01:32:03.460
[Guest]: gets regional parties, which are ideologically very similar to it, Congress parties almost

01:32:03.460 --> 01:32:08.780
[Guest]: finished in that state. You quoted the example of Tamil Nadu, what Congress was basically

01:32:08.780 --> 01:32:16.140
[Guest]: doing was one time aligning with DMK one time aligning with with AIDMK. Basically, Congress

01:32:16.140 --> 01:32:22.340
[Guest]: Party gets caught between AIDMK and DMK and is now virtually not a player in Tamil Nadu.

01:32:22.340 --> 01:32:28.060
[Guest]: Something very similar happens in Uttar Pradesh, Congress Party basically is squeezed by both

01:32:28.060 --> 01:32:34.340
[Guest]: the presence of the Samajwadi Party and Bahujan Samaj Party and come to think of it. The reason

01:32:34.340 --> 01:32:40.300
[Guest]: is that Congress, it is hard to distinguish ideologically on the question of recognition

01:32:40.300 --> 01:32:46.020
[Guest]: and on the question of statism. So these parties are indistinguishable from the Congress Party.

01:32:46.020 --> 01:32:50.420
[Guest]: In fact, Congress Party survives in the state and does well in the state where it is in

01:32:50.420 --> 01:32:54.620
[Guest]: direct competition with the BJP. Think of Madhya Pradesh, think of Rajasthan, think

01:32:54.620 --> 01:32:59.540
[Guest]: of Chhattisgarh, think of Himachal Pradesh. In all these states, the direct competition

01:32:59.540 --> 01:33:04.100
[Guest]: of the Congress is BJP. And these two parties are ideologically very different.

01:33:04.100 --> 01:33:08.700
[Amit Varma]: So therefore, it can survive when you know, it has that positioning advantage otherwise

01:33:08.700 --> 01:33:09.700
[Guest]: is

01:33:09.700 --> 01:33:15.220
[Guest]: Yeah, and we use this example to make the point that a lot of people think that the

01:33:15.220 --> 01:33:22.540
[Guest]: decline of the Congress was is due to leadership, or due to organizational atrophy. And if these

01:33:22.540 --> 01:33:27.180
[Guest]: two were the reasons you have the same leader, you have the similar organization, but the

01:33:27.180 --> 01:33:33.500
[Guest]: decline of Congress varies across Indian state, depending upon who is Congress Party's main

01:33:33.500 --> 01:33:39.620
[Guest]: competitor. Right. So you see one kind of Congress, which is alive and kicking when

01:33:39.620 --> 01:33:45.420
[Guest]: it competes with the BJP, but another Congress kind of Congress Party, which is now defunct

01:33:45.420 --> 01:33:50.780
[Guest]: in states like UP, Bihar, Bengal and Tamil Nadu, where you are competing with regional

01:33:50.780 --> 01:33:51.780
[Amit Varma]: parties.

01:33:51.780 --> 01:33:57.900
[Amit Varma]: So now in this third party phase, the two big M words that come up here are Mandal and

01:33:57.900 --> 01:34:03.900
[Amit Varma]: Mandir. So tell me how the resurgence of Mandir and the arrival of Mandal, how do they play

01:34:03.900 --> 01:34:09.300
[Amit Varma]: in this ideological landscape of recognition and statism? And how does that bring the lead

01:34:09.300 --> 01:34:11.740
[Amit Varma]: into the fourth era, which we're in right now?

01:34:11.740 --> 01:34:18.460
[Guest]: So in the book, basically, we mentioned about that perhaps 2014 is the arrival of the fourth

01:34:18.460 --> 01:34:23.620
[Guest]: party system, where BJP is going to become the focal point of competition. And now the

01:34:23.620 --> 01:34:30.220
[Guest]: 2019 results basically confirm that we are indeed in a BJP dominant party system. What

01:34:30.220 --> 01:34:38.420
[Guest]: happens, you mentioned these Mandir and Mandal, which simultaneously occurs in between 1989

01:34:38.420 --> 01:34:47.300
[Guest]: and 1991. Now, Congress Party on both questions remains ambivalent. In fact, so think of the

01:34:47.300 --> 01:34:52.020
[Guest]: politics that is emerging, right? Somebody tells Rajiv Gandhi, the Prime Minister that

01:34:52.020 --> 01:34:59.860
[Guest]: you lost the by polls in 1986. Because you, there was some controversy related to Shah

01:34:59.860 --> 01:35:05.980
[Guest]: Bano case, and you didn't do enough. Rajiv Gandhi, in fact, sort of like, twist the parliament's

01:35:05.980 --> 01:35:14.180
[Guest]: hand and passes a law. So he's basically sometimes playing with the Muslim conservative politicians.

01:35:14.180 --> 01:35:21.040
[Guest]: And at other times, he's trying to be a liberal reformist. Then someone basically tells him

01:35:21.040 --> 01:35:26.420
[Guest]: perhaps that now the Muslims are gone, you should think about Hindu conservative politician.

01:35:26.420 --> 01:35:33.420
[Guest]: So Rajiv Gandhi basically begins the 1989 election campaigns from Ayodhya. So basically,

01:35:33.420 --> 01:35:41.580
[Guest]: playing with fire, trying to do both the things, whereas the BJP takes a very clear position

01:35:41.580 --> 01:35:47.860
[Guest]: on both the issue. They don't say much, at least publicly on the question of Mandir reservation,

01:35:47.860 --> 01:35:52.580
[Guest]: because they know it would be an electoral society to oppose reservation for such a large

01:35:52.580 --> 01:35:59.740
[Guest]: group. But they do prop up proxy opposition to Mandir reservation and to counter the effects

01:35:59.740 --> 01:36:06.060
[Guest]: of Mandir reservation, in fact, join the bandwagon of Mandir mobilization. So Ram Mandir mobilization

01:36:06.060 --> 01:36:11.740
[Guest]: was happening at the backdrop through Vishwa Hindu Parishad and other RSS affiliates since

01:36:11.740 --> 01:36:18.540
[Guest]: early 1980s. After the Meenakshi Puram conversion in 1982, it gained momentum during late 80s.

01:36:18.540 --> 01:36:23.660
[Guest]: And this seemed like a good opportunity for them to counter the effects of Mandir and

01:36:23.660 --> 01:36:30.780
[Guest]: create a pan Hindu identity. So because BJP took some sort of like clear position, the

01:36:30.780 --> 01:36:38.900
[Guest]: first effect of that was that the upper caste basically thought that this party takes care

01:36:38.900 --> 01:36:45.060
[Guest]: of their ideological platforms. They left Congress en masse in the Hindi heartland and

01:36:45.060 --> 01:36:51.340
[Guest]: joined the BJP. Congress is not doing so is ambivalent on these positions, whereas regional

01:36:51.340 --> 01:36:58.900
[Guest]: parties were clear, like the SP was clear on the question of reservation, and also in

01:36:58.900 --> 01:37:07.700
[Guest]: some ways, sided on the position which Muslims would have wanted them to take on Ram Mandir

01:37:07.700 --> 01:37:12.820
[Guest]: mobilization. And they got the benefit of that. So there were two parties which took

01:37:12.820 --> 01:37:18.540
[Guest]: clear position, the Congress didn't do anything. And that's why basically Congress slowly faded

01:37:18.540 --> 01:37:21.740
[Guest]: in the Hindi heartland of UP and Bihar.

01:37:21.740 --> 01:37:24.060
[Guest]: So bring me now to the fourth party era.

01:37:24.060 --> 01:37:32.460
[Guest]: So in 2014, what you see is emergence of BJP as the principal pole of Indian politics.

01:37:32.460 --> 01:37:40.860
[Guest]: And 2019 basically now cements the BJP's pole position. Now, what is likely to happen, and

01:37:40.860 --> 01:37:46.060
[Guest]: this is a working paper on 2019 elections from where I'm sort of like going to make

01:37:46.060 --> 01:37:53.340
[Guest]: the case that it seems and so far the conversation seems on short term factors which led to Modi's

01:37:53.340 --> 01:37:57.860
[Guest]: victory, which is basically the leadership popularity, the organizational advantages

01:37:57.860 --> 01:38:05.140
[Guest]: BJP has, or their successful presentation of 2019 as a national election and using national

01:38:05.140 --> 01:38:11.780
[Guest]: security platform, or basically removing inconveniences through massive welfare schemes such as Ujjwala

01:38:11.780 --> 01:38:18.220
[Guest]: and other things. While these factors are definitely important, the reason I think BJP

01:38:18.220 --> 01:38:24.260
[Guest]: is becoming the dominant pole of Indian politics is large structural shifts that are taking

01:38:24.260 --> 01:38:30.420
[Guest]: place in Indian society. The first one is very simply that the size of the middle class

01:38:30.420 --> 01:38:34.860
[Guest]: is increasing, the size of the urban population is increasing, the size of educated voters

01:38:34.860 --> 01:38:40.660
[Guest]: is increasing, the size of people who are more media, sort of like exposed to more media

01:38:40.660 --> 01:38:41.660
[Amit Varma]: is increasing.

01:38:41.660 --> 01:38:45.140
[Amit Varma]: And these guys are likely to be against both statism and recognition.

01:38:45.140 --> 01:38:51.740
[Guest]: These guys are essentially, in some ways, BJP voters. And so what is happening is that

01:38:51.740 --> 01:38:59.500
[Guest]: the size of the BJP, the pie from which BJP can draw is increasing, but just increase

01:38:59.500 --> 01:39:07.140
[Guest]: in demographic share does not mean that they are more likely to vote for the BJP. The second

01:39:07.140 --> 01:39:14.340
[Guest]: thing I think what is happening is basically on, so we don't have good evidence on statism,

01:39:14.340 --> 01:39:23.340
[Guest]: but there is clear clarity on politics of recognition scale playing a role in basically

01:39:23.340 --> 01:39:28.820
[Guest]: bringing these new groups to the BJP fold. One, I think what is happening, political

01:39:28.820 --> 01:39:36.740
[Guest]: majoritarianism is increasing. And second, the BJP's use of this EWS quota to change

01:39:36.740 --> 01:39:43.580
[Guest]: the whole debate on recognition and affirmative action is bringing these new group of voters.

01:39:43.580 --> 01:39:49.780
[Guest]: And what is interesting, and I don't have a good answer right now, it seems that political

01:39:49.780 --> 01:39:56.500
[Guest]: majoritarianism is not linked to Hindu nationalism. And why this point is important, because if

01:39:56.500 --> 01:40:02.900
[Guest]: it was old style Hindu nationalistic politics, I don't think you would have got an increase

01:40:02.900 --> 01:40:10.060
[Guest]: in vote share of Dalits and lower OBCs for the BJP. So I think the old Hindu nationalistic

01:40:10.060 --> 01:40:18.260
[Guest]: card was rooted in upper caste sensibilities, whereas this new Modi's political majoritarianism

01:40:18.260 --> 01:40:24.540
[Guest]: is devoid of those upper caste biases. And it's a new kind of sort of majority.

01:40:24.540 --> 01:40:28.580
[Amit Varma]: I mean, he's an OBC himself. And as you point out in your book, some of the reasons for

01:40:28.580 --> 01:40:33.140
[Amit Varma]: the rise of an OBC like Modi to power and the BJP have to do with Govind Acharya's decision

01:40:33.140 --> 01:40:40.380
[Amit Varma]: in the 90s to sort of widen the social base of the BJP, which, you know, brings me to

01:40:40.380 --> 01:40:44.260
[Amit Varma]: two questions, I'll kind of end the episode with because we're running out of time. But

01:40:44.260 --> 01:40:48.980
[Amit Varma]: you know, there are tons of fascinating material in your book. Another question I wanted to

01:40:48.980 --> 01:40:54.100
[Amit Varma]: ask was, you've got a very good analysis about the decline of the Congress and why many of

01:40:54.100 --> 01:40:58.620
[Amit Varma]: the traditional reasons sorted out by people don't necessarily work. But as we don't have

01:40:58.620 --> 01:41:03.220
[Amit Varma]: time for that in this episode, but I hope my listeners will go by your book instantly

01:41:03.220 --> 01:41:08.540
[Amit Varma]: and read it, support good scholarship. But both my questions are essentially about the

01:41:08.540 --> 01:41:14.940
[Amit Varma]: BJP. One of them is that one of the things that Amit Shah has been doing as a political

01:41:14.940 --> 01:41:21.340
[Amit Varma]: strategist is sort of widening the base, but widening the base can also in some ways mean

01:41:21.340 --> 01:41:27.740
[Amit Varma]: diluting the ideology or what the party stands for. For example, they are getting sort of

01:41:27.740 --> 01:41:33.060
[Amit Varma]: defections from other parties almost indiscriminately now anyone who wishes to join and can bring

01:41:33.060 --> 01:41:37.780
[Amit Varma]: a base with him just join. And then that, you know, so it's a question of will to power

01:41:37.780 --> 01:41:42.340
[Amit Varma]: versus ideology. The will to power is fantastic. But doesn't this dilute the ideology and what

01:41:42.340 --> 01:41:48.500
[Amit Varma]: the party actually stands for? Question number one. And question number two, as you point

01:41:48.500 --> 01:41:53.380
[Amit Varma]: out the increasing urbanization of and this was one of the very interesting points towards

01:41:53.380 --> 01:41:59.540
[Amit Varma]: the end of your book, that the increasing urbanization of India makes another kind of

01:41:59.540 --> 01:42:09.040
[Amit Varma]: fissure apparent, where a lot of the people who sort of support Modi for multiple reasons

01:42:09.040 --> 01:42:13.780
[Amit Varma]: now will not have those multiple reasons to support him in future. So just elaborate on

01:42:13.780 --> 01:42:14.780
[Guest]: that.

01:42:14.780 --> 01:42:21.260
[Guest]: That's correct. I think so BJP is now a dominant party, but will it remain a dominant party

01:42:21.260 --> 01:42:26.980
[Guest]: for a long time? They need to so there are emerging contradictions within the coalition

01:42:26.980 --> 01:42:32.100
[Guest]: that has brought BJP to power and they have to work on it. You are absolutely right about

01:42:32.100 --> 01:42:38.500
[Guest]: basically BJP taking in politicians from outside and whether it would dilute ideology. Now

01:42:38.500 --> 01:42:44.140
[Guest]: that remains an open question because political parties are not just there to sort of like

01:42:44.140 --> 01:42:48.580
[Guest]: follow an ideological doctrine, but primary reason they exist because they want to be

01:42:48.580 --> 01:42:54.700
[Guest]: in power. So given that there is some sort of like vulnerability factor associated in

01:42:54.700 --> 01:43:00.620
[Guest]: bringing these politicians, all political parties would do that. But is BJP going to

01:43:00.620 --> 01:43:06.460
[Guest]: sort of like allow these new kind of politicians to run the show and not tow its ideological

01:43:06.460 --> 01:43:11.140
[Guest]: line? I think if they do that, they would be in trouble with their ideological sort

01:43:11.140 --> 01:43:17.900
[Guest]: of like fountainhead and there would be sticks from Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh. In fact,

01:43:17.900 --> 01:43:22.980
[Guest]: there have been warning signs after this election. They are continuously trying to push back

01:43:22.980 --> 01:43:28.260
[Guest]: that don't make it a personality centric government or personality centric election or on personality.

01:43:28.260 --> 01:43:35.500
[Guest]: This is a victory of our ideas. The second point I think we must sort of like keep this

01:43:35.500 --> 01:43:40.900
[Guest]: in mind and that that happens with all political parties. When you expand, you bring in not

01:43:40.900 --> 01:43:46.060
[Guest]: just different sort of like politicians who don't share your ideology, but you also bring

01:43:46.060 --> 01:43:51.980
[Guest]: voters who are not part of your core support group. Now, they will come to you and vote

01:43:51.980 --> 01:43:56.660
[Guest]: for you, but they would want something in return. They would want representation. This

01:43:56.660 --> 01:44:01.740
[Guest]: is what happened with the Congress parties in 1970s. It was getting vote from all segments

01:44:01.740 --> 01:44:08.140
[Guest]: of the society, but large part of Congress leadership remained upper caste. So basically,

01:44:08.140 --> 01:44:12.860
[Guest]: many leaders moved out and formed different political parties and the decline of the Congress

01:44:12.860 --> 01:44:19.860
[Guest]: thus began. It would happen with the BJP also, if the party remains upper caste in its leadership

01:44:19.860 --> 01:44:27.260
[Guest]: structure. For some time, when you have a charismatic personality like Modi, these contradictions

01:44:27.260 --> 01:44:34.860
[Guest]: would be sort of like subdued. But once someone like Modi goes and you don't have a replacement,

01:44:34.860 --> 01:44:40.740
[Guest]: these would unravel like anything. The final point, which is important, that we have to

01:44:40.740 --> 01:44:46.980
[Guest]: understand the changing context in India. So, BJP in some ways practices conservative

01:44:46.980 --> 01:44:53.940
[Guest]: politics on social norms, but large segment of voters which are voting for BJP are receiving

01:44:53.940 --> 01:45:00.380
[Guest]: global messages and as much we will get integrated into global economy, they would receive very

01:45:00.380 --> 01:45:05.420
[Guest]: different kind of messages and aspire very different kind of life. So, they might be

01:45:05.420 --> 01:45:13.620
[Guest]: voting Modi for fulfillment of certain aspirations. But if on other parameters, they feel threatened

01:45:13.620 --> 01:45:20.060
[Guest]: by the politics of BJP, that would create its own sort of like contradictions and fissures.

01:45:20.060 --> 01:45:26.740
[Guest]: And I think that is where the BJP's challenge lies, to be able to manage these contradictions

01:45:26.740 --> 01:45:29.700
[Guest]: and hold on to the ideological coalition they have created.

01:45:29.700 --> 01:45:34.980
[Amit Varma]: In fact, you could argue that, you know, the fact that they won in 2014 and 2019 is almost

01:45:34.980 --> 01:45:39.860
[Amit Varma]: like a perfect storm of events coming together, managing to draw all these disparate social

01:45:39.860 --> 01:45:45.180
[Amit Varma]: groups who are not yet this enamored of the BJP. And there's a telling line from your

01:45:45.180 --> 01:45:48.740
[Amit Varma]: book when you talk about the growing urban voter where you say, quote, the young may

01:45:48.740 --> 01:45:54.100
[Amit Varma]: hold their noses and vote for the BJP, especially because of a lack of credible ideological

01:45:54.100 --> 01:45:59.500
[Amit Varma]: alternatives. But this support will not last because this group is not enamored of majoritarian

01:45:59.500 --> 01:46:04.020
[Amit Varma]: politics. Stop quote, which is interesting. And is it also the case that there might be

01:46:04.020 --> 01:46:11.820
[Amit Varma]: people who might feel that the BJP led by Modi in this sort of broad based avatar is

01:46:11.820 --> 01:46:14.460
[Amit Varma]: not doing enough for the Hindu cause?

01:46:14.460 --> 01:46:15.460
[Amit Varma]: It is possible.

